{"title_page": "David Koch", "text_new": "{{About|the American businessman||}}\n{{short description|American billionaire heir and businessman}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = David Koch\n| image       = David Koch by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption     = Koch in 2015\n| birth_name  = David Hamilton Koch\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1940|5|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Wichita, Kansas]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2019|8|23|1940|5|3}}\n| death_place = [[Southampton, New York]], U.S.\n| education   = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Bachelor of Science|SB]], [[Master of Science|SM]])\n| occupation  = Vice president of [[Koch Industries]]\n| known_for   = Philanthropy to cultural and medical institutions<br />Support of libertarian and conservative causes<ref name=\"Mayer\" /><ref name=\"Wallet\">{{Cite news |url=https://nymag.com/news/features/67285/ |title=The Billionaire's Party: David Koch is New York's second-richest man, a celebrated patron of the arts, and the tea party's wallet |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=July 25, 2010 |first=Andrew |last=Goldman |access-date=August 26, 2010}}</ref>\n| party       = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] (before 1984)<br />[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (1984\u20132019)\n| boards      = [[Aspen Institute]], [[Cato Institute]], [[Reason Foundation]], [[Americans for Prosperity|Americans for Prosperity Foundation]], [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]], [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History]], [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], [[American Ballet Theatre]], [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]], [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]], [[American Museum of Natural History]]\n| spouse      = {{Marriage|Julia Flesher Koch|1996}}\n| children    = 3\n| parents     = [[Fred C. Koch]]<br />Mary Robinson\n| relatives   = [[Frederick R. Koch]] (brother)<br />[[Charles Koch]] (brother)<br />[[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill Koch]] (twin brother)\n| networth    = [[United States dollar|US$]]48&nbsp;billion (June 2019)\n}}\n\n'''David Hamilton Koch''' ({{IPAc-en|k|o\u028a|k}}; May 3, 1940&nbsp;\u2013 August 23, 2019) was an American businessman, philanthropist, political activist, and chemical engineer. In 1970, he joined the family business: [[Koch Industries]], the second-largest privately held company in the United States. He became president of the subsidiary Koch Engineering in 1979, and became a co-owner of Koch Industries (along with elder brother [[Charles Koch|Charles]]) in 1983. Koch served as an executive vice president of Koch Industries until he retired due to health issues in 2018.\n\nKoch was a [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]]. He was the 1980 [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] candidate for [[Vice President of the United States]] and helped finance the campaign. He founded [[Citizens for a Sound Economy]] and donated to advocacy groups and [[Political activities of the Koch brothers|political campaigns]], most of which were [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. Koch became a Republican in 1984; in 2012, he spent over $100&nbsp;million to oppose the re-election of President [[Barack Obama]].\n\nKoch was the fourth-richest person in the United States in 2012 and was the wealthiest resident of [[New York City]] in 2013. As of June 2019, Koch was ranked as the 11th-richest person in the world (tied with his brother Charles), with a fortune of $50.5&nbsp;billion. Known for his philanthropy, Koch contributed to the [[Lincoln Center]], [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center|Sloan Kettering]], [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]], and the Dinosaur Wing at the [[American Museum of Natural History]]. The New York State Theater at Lincoln Center, home of the [[New York City Ballet]], was renamed the [[David H. Koch Theater]] in 2008 following Koch's gift of $100&nbsp;million for the renovation of the theater.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKoch was born in [[Wichita, Kansas]], the son of Mary Clementine (n\u00e9e Robinson) and [[Fred C. Koch|Fred Chase Koch]], a chemical engineer. David's paternal grandfather, [[Harry Koch (businessman)|Harry Koch]], was a Dutch immigrant who founded the ''Quanah Tribune-Chief'' newspaper and was a founding shareholder of the [[Quanah, Acme and Pacific Railway]].<ref name=\"new netherland\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nnp.org/nni/Publications/Dutch-American/kochd.htm |title=Koch, David Hamilton (1940) |publisher=New Netherland Project |access-date=August 31, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819225843/http://www.nnp.org/nni/Publications/Dutch-American/kochd.htm |archive-date=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> David was the third of four sons, with elder brothers [[Frederick R. Koch|Frederick]], Charles, and nineteen-minute-younger twin<ref name=\"kochbtp\" /> [[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill]]. His maternal ancestors included [[William Ingraham Kip]], an Episcopal bishop; [[William Burnet Kinney]], a politician; and [[Elizabeth Clementine Stedman]], a writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.palmbeachdailynews.com/obituaries/20190824/palm-beach-obituary-bill-koch-remembers-brother-david-as-rsquooutstanding-human-best-friendrsquo|title=Palm Beach obituary: Bill Koch remembers brother David as 'outstanding human, best friend'|first=Shannon|last=Donnelly|website=Palm Beach Daily News}}</ref>\n\nKoch attended the [[Deerfield Academy]] prep school in Massachusetts, graduating in 1959. He attended [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), earning both a [[bachelor's degree|bachelor's]] (1962) and a [[master's degree]] (1963) in [[chemical engineering]]. He was a member of the [[Beta Theta Pi]] fraternity. Koch played basketball at MIT, averaging 21 points per game at MIT over three years, a school record. He also held the single-game scoring record of 41 points from 1962 until 2009, when it was eclipsed by [[Jimmy Bartolotta]].<ref name=\"kochbtp\">{{Cite journal |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/114135/david-and-william-koch-mit-basketball-players |title=David and William Koch as MIT Basketball Players |journal=The New Republic |date=August 14, 2013 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career at Koch Industries ==\nIn 1970, Koch joined [[Koch Industries]] under his brother [[Charles Koch|Charles]], to work as a technical-services manager. He founded the company's New York City office and in 1979 he became the president of his own division, Koch Engineering, renamed Chemical Technology Group. David's brothers [[Frederick R. Koch|Frederick]] and [[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill]] had inherited stock in Koch Industries. In June 1983, after a bitter legal and boardroom battle, the stakes of Frederick and Bill were bought out for $1.1&nbsp;billion and Charles Koch and David Koch became majority owners in the company.<ref>{{Cite news | url= https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/28/business/brother-versus-brother-koch-family-s-long-legal-feud-is-headed-for-a-jury.html | title=Brother Versus Brother; Koch Family's Long Legal Feud Is Headed for a Jury | first=Leslie | last= Wayne | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 28, 1998 | url-status=live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180326160300/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/28/business/brother-versus-brother-koch-family-s-long-legal-feud-is-headed-for-a-jury.html | archivedate=March 26, 2018 | df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=MorningSun>\"Koch's wife granted order of restraint\". Pittsburg (KS) ''Morning Sun'', July 21, 2000.</ref> Legal disputes against Charles and David lasted roughly two decades. Frederick and Bill sided with [[J. Howard Marshall III]], [[J. Howard Marshall II]]'s eldest son, against Charles and David at one point, in order to take over the company. In 2001, Bill reached a settlement in a lawsuit where he had charged the company was taking oil from federal and Indian land; that settlement ended all litigation between the brothers.<ref name=WallStreet>\"Judge Clears Koch Brothers' Settlement Pact\". ''Wall Street Journal'', May 29, 2001.</ref> CBS News reported that Koch Industries settled for $25&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/11/27/60II/main252545.shtml |title=Blood And Oil |publisher=CBS News |date=2000-11-27 |access-date=2015-10-15}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2010, David Koch owned 42 percent of Koch Industries, as did his brother Charles.<ref name=Wallet /> He held four U.S patents.<ref name=\"TimeObit\">{{Cite news |url=https://time.com/5660040/david-koch-legacy/ |title=David Koch's Millions Remade the Republican Party. He Didn't Like the Results |work=Time |date=August 23, 2019 |first=Philip | last=Elliott}}</ref> Koch served as an executive vice president of Koch Industries until retiring due to health issues in 2018.<ref name=\"asgbio\">http://www.theadvocates.org/celebrities/david-koch.html {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070226111813/http://www.theadvocates.org/celebrities/david-koch.html|date=February 26, 2007}}</ref> His retirement was announced on June 5, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/06/05/david-koch-is-leaving-koch-industries-stepping-down-from-americans-for-prosperity/ |title=David Koch is leaving Koch Industries, stepping down from Americans for Prosperity |first=James |last=Hohmann |date=June 5, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=June 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political involvement ==\n{{See also|Political activities of the Koch brothers}}\n\n===Campaigns===\nKoch was the [[United States Libertarian Party|Libertarian Party]]'s [[Vice President of the United States|vice-presidential]] candidate in the [[1980 United States presidential election|1980 presidential election]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=Man Without a Candidate |authorlink=Charlotte Curtis |first=Charlotte |last=Curtis |date=October 16, 1984 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/16/arts/man-without-a-candidate.html |access-date=July 18, 2015}}</ref> sharing the party ticket with [[President of the United States|presidential]] candidate [[Ed Clark]]. The Clark\u2013Koch [[Ticket (election)|ticket]] promised to abolish [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], the [[Federal Reserve Board]], [[welfare]], [[minimum-wage]] laws, corporate taxes, all price supports and subsidies for agriculture and business, and [[U.S. Federal agencies]] including the SEC, EPA, ICC, FTC, OSHA, FBI, CIA, and DOE.<ref name=\"Mayer\" /><ref name=Buck>Rinker Buck, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ueUCAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA18&dq=David%20Koch&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q=David%20Koch&f=false \"How Those Libertarians Pay the Bills\"], [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]], November 3, 1980</ref> The ticket received 921,128 votes, 1% of the total nationwide vote,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1980&off=0&f=1|title=1980 Presidential General Election Results|first=David | last=Leip |publisher=uselectionatlas.org}}</ref> the Libertarian Party national ticket's best showing until [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] in terms of percentage and its best showing in terms of raw votes until the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 presidential election]], although that number was surpassed again in 2016.<ref name=Bennett>James T. Bennett, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eImBSPX63D0C&pg=PA167&dq=ed+clark+highest+vote+total+1980&hl=en&ei=YZB9TMd3goHyBufjrZkH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=ed%20clark%20highest%20vote%20total%201980&f=false ''Not Invited to the Party: How the Demopublicans Have Rigged the System and Left Independents Out in the Cold''], Springer, 2009, p. 167, {{ISBN|1-4419-0365-8}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Quixotic '80 Campaign Gave Birth to Kochs' Powerful Network |authorlink=Nicholas Confessore |first=Nicholas |last=Confessore |date=May 17, 2014 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/18/us/politics/quixotic-80-campaign-gave-birth-to-kochs-powerful-network.html |access-date=July 18, 2015 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> \"Compared to what [the Libertarians had] gotten before,\" Charles said, \"and where we were as a movement or as a political/ideological point of view, that was pretty remarkable, to get 1 percent of the vote.\"<ref name=Continetti>{{Cite news|first=Matthew |last=Continetti|authorlink=Matthew Continetti|title=The Paranoid Style in Liberal Politics|work=[[The Weekly Standard]]|date=April 4, 2011|url=https://www.weeklystandard.com/matthew-continetti/the-paranoid-style-in-liberal-politics}}</ref>\n\nAfter the bid, according to journalist [[Brian Doherty (journalist)|Brian Doherty]]'s ''[[Radicals for Capitalism]]'', Koch viewed politicians as \"actors playing out a script.\"<ref name=Mayer /><ref name=\"Doherty2008\">{{Cite book|last=Doherty|first=Brian |authorlink=Brian Doherty (journalist)|title=Radicals for Capitalism: A Freewheeling History of the Modern American Libertarian Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6g_NGAAACAAJ|access-date=October 10, 2011|date=May 26, 2008|publisher=Perseus Books Group|isbn=978-1-58648-572-6|page=410}}</ref>\n\nKoch credited the 1976 presidential campaign of [[Roger MacBride]] as his inspiration for getting involved in politics:\n\n<blockquote style=font-size:100%>Here was a great guy, advocating all the things I believed in. He wanted less government and taxes, and was talking about repealing all these victimless crime laws that accumulated on the books. I have friends who smoke pot. I know many homosexuals. It's ridiculous to treat them as criminals&nbsp;\u2014 and here was someone running for president, saying just that.<ref name=Buck /></blockquote>\n\nKoch gave his own vice presidential campaign $100,000 a month after being chosen as [[Ed Clark]]'s running mate. \"We'd like to abolish the [[Federal Elections Commission]] and all the limits on campaign spending anyway,\" Koch said in 1980. When asked why he ran, he replied: \"Lord knows I didn't need a job, but I believe in what the Libertarians are saying. I suppose if they hadn't come along, I could have been a big Republican from [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]]. But hell&nbsp;\u2014 ''everybody'' from Kansas is a Republican.\"<ref name=Buck />\n\nIn 1984, Koch broke with the Libertarian Party when it supported eliminating all taxes. Subsequently, Koch was a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].<ref name=Wallet />{{Rp|4}} Koch donated  \nto various [[Political activities of the Koch brothers|political campaigns]], most of which were [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/orgs/summary.php?id=D000000186&cycle=A |title=Koch Industries: Summary |publisher=OpenSecrets.org |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> In February 2012, during the [[Wisconsin gubernatorial recall election]], Koch said of Wisconsin governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], \"We're helping him, as we should. We've gotten pretty good at this over the years. We've spent a lot of money in Wisconsin. We're going to spend more,\" and said that by \"we\" he meant Americans for Prosperity.<ref>{{Cite news |title=David Koch intends to cure cancer in his lifetime and remake American politics |date=February 20, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/business/david-koch-intends-to-cure-cancer-in-his-lifetime-/nL4Fb/ |first=Stacey |last=Singer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |magazine=[[The Nation]] |authorlink=John Nichols (journalist) |first=John |last=Nichols |title=Scott Walker's Koch Connection Goes Bad |date=February 24, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/166450/scott-walkers-koch-connection-goes-bad}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Billionaire Koch brothers gave $8&nbsp;million to Wisconsin Gov. Scott Walker recall campaign, Dem chair says |first=Tom |last=Kertscher |date=June 20, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |url=http://www.politifact.com/wisconsin/statements/2012/jun/20/debbie-wasserman-schultz/billionaire-koch-brothers-gave-8-million-wisconsin/ |publisher=[[PolitiFact]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |magazine=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |title=How Did Wisconsin Become the Most Politically Divisive Place in America? |first=Dan |last=Kaufman |date=May 24, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/27/magazine/how-did-wisconsin-become-the-most-politically-divisive-place-in-america.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=On Politics: David Koch: 'We've spent a lot of money in Wisconsin. We're going to spend more.' |date=February 20, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |first=Mary |last=Spicuzza |newspaper=[[Wisconsin State Journal]] |url=http://host.madison.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/on-politics/on-politics-david-koch-we-ve-spent-a-lot-of/article_dc909fe4-5bde-11e1-a0db-0019bb2963f4.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Koch spent over $100&nbsp;million to oppose the re-election of President [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/15/us/politics/122-million-in-2012-spending-by-koch-group.html |title=$122 Million in 2012 Spending by Koch Group |last=Confessore |first=Nicholas |date=2013-11-14 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2019-08-25 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tariniparti/billionaire-david-koch-dies |title=Billionaire David Koch, Who Shaped Modern Conservative Politics, Has Died |access-date=2019-08-25 |publisher=[[BuzzFeed News]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Views ===\nKoch supported policies that promote [[individual liberty]] and [[free market]] principles, and supported reducing government spending.<ref name=\"kochnyt\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/05/us/05koch.html|date=March 5, 2011 |work=The New York Times|title=Cancer Research Before Activism, Billionaire Conservative Donor Says|last=Cooper|first=Michael}}</ref><ref>The Koch Brothers December 24, 2012 p. 96 Forbes</ref> Koch supported a [[non-interventionist]] foreign policy; \"Pursuing a very aggressive foreign policy,\" he said, \"is an extremely expensive endeavor for the U.S. government. The cost of maintaining a huge military force abroad is gigantic. It's so big it puts a severe strain on the U.S. economy, creating economic hardships here at home.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://reason.com/archives/1987/02/01/the-new-antiwar-capitalists/print|title=The New Antiwar Capitalists|website=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref> Koch opposed the [[Iraq War]], saying that the war has \"cost a lot of money and it's taken so many American lives\", and \"I question whether that was the right thing to do. In hindsight that looks like it was not a good policy.\"<ref name=Continetti /> In an impromptu interview with the blog ThinkProgress, he was quoted as saying he would like the new, 2011 Republican Congress to \"cut the hell out of spending, balance the budget, reduce regulations, and support business.\"<ref name=\"kochtp\">{{Cite news |url=http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2011/01/06/137586/koch-teaparty-us/|publisher=ThinkProgress|date=January 6, 2011|last=Fang |first=Lee|title=Exclusive: Polluter Billionaire David Koch Says Tea Party 'Rank And File Are Just Normal People Like Us'}}</ref> He was against the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and the Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act.<ref name=\"Wallet\" /> He was skeptical about anthropogenic [[global warming]]. He said a warmer planet would be good, because \"Earth will be able to support enormously more people, because a far greater land area will be available to produce food\".<ref name=\"Wallet\" /> Koch considered himself a [[Cultural liberalism|social liberal]]<ref name=\"Bell\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2014/12/billionaire-david-koch-says-hes-a-social-liberal/ |title=Billionaire David Koch Says He's a Social Liberal|publisher=ABC News|date=December 14, 2014|access-date=December 29, 2014|first=Benjamin | last=Bell}}</ref> who supported women's [[right to choose]],<ref name=\"Fischer\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/14/politics/david-koch-gay-rights-abortion-democrats/ |title=David Koch is pro-choice, supports gay rights; just not Democrats|publisher=CNN|date=December 15, 2014 |access-date=December 29, 2014|first=Sara | last=Fischer}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]], [[same-sex marriage]] and [[stem-cell research]].<ref name=\"Wallet\" /><ref>Joseph Patrick McCormick, [http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/09/02/billionaire-gop-supporter-disagrees-with-platform-says-he-supports-gay-marriage/ Billionaire GOP supporter disagrees with platform, says he supports gay marriage], ''[[PinkNews]]'', September 2, 2012</ref> He opposed the [[war on drugs]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coaston |first1=Jane |title=\"David Koch walked the walk\": a libertarian on the Koch brother\u2019s legacy |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/8/23/20829962/david-koch-libertarian-legacy |publisher=Vox |accessdate=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nKoch opposed several of President [[Barack Obama|Barack Obama's]] policies. An article from the ''[[Weekly Standard]]'', detailing the \"left's obsession\" with the Koch brothers, quotes Koch stating that Obama is \"the most radical president we've ever had as a nation ... and has done more damage to the free enterprise system and long-term prosperity than any president we've ever had.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/articles/paranoid-style-liberal-politics_555525.html?nopager=1|title=The Paranoid Style in Liberal Politics|work=[[The Weekly Standard]]}}</ref> Koch said that Obama's father's economic [[socialism]], practiced in [[Kenya]], explains why Obama has \"sort of antibusiness and anti-free enterprise\" influences.<ref name=Continetti /> Koch said that Obama is \"scary\", a \"hardcore socialist\" who is \"marvelous at pretending to be something other than that.\"<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite news |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intel/2011/05/billionaire_conservative_david.html|title=David Koch Gives President Obama Zero Credit for Bin Laden's Death|work=New York|first=Sarah|last=Owen|date=May 5, 2011}}</ref> Koch contributed almost entirely to Republican candidates in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/11/charts-map-koch-brothers-2012-spending|title=Charts: How Much Have the Kochs Spent on the 2012 Election?|work=Mother Jones}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nKoch donated funds to various advocacy groups.<ref name=\"Wallet\" /> In 1984, he founded [[Citizens for a Sound Economy]] (CSE).<ref name=Mazur>Suzan Mazur, [https://books.google.com/books?id=wk2FfQQ_DmsC&pg=PA244 \"The Altenberg 16: An Expos\u00e9 of the Evolution Industry\"], ''North Atlantic Books'', 2010, 343 pages</ref> He served as its Chairman of the [[board of directors]] and donated funds to it. [[Richard H. Fink]] served as its first president.<ref name=Continetti /> Koch was the chairman of the board and gave initial funding to the [[Americans for Prosperity|Americans for Prosperity Foundation]] and to a related advocacy organization, [[Americans for Prosperity]]. A Koch Industries spokesperson issued a press release stating \"No funding has been provided by Koch companies, the Koch foundations, or Charles Koch or David Koch specifically to support the tea parties.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/08/30/covert-operations|title=Covert Operations|first=Jane | last=Mayer |date=August 30, 2010 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref><ref name=\"WeigelFW\">{{Cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/04/dick_armey_please_koch_keep_di.html |first=David | last=Weigel |title=Dick Armey: Please, Koch, keep distancing yourself from me |work=The Washington Post |date=April 15, 2010}}</ref> Koch was the top initial funder of the Americans for Prosperity Foundation at $850,000.<ref>{{Cite news |title=David Koch Seeded Major Tea-Party Group, Private Donor List Reveals |first=Alex |last=Seitz-Wald |date=September 24, 2013 |access-date=March 20, 2015 |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/politics/david-koch-seeded-major-tea-party-group-private-donor-list-reveals-20130924 |work=[[National Journal]] |quote=But a donor list filed with the IRS labeled \"not open for public inspection\" from 2003, the year of AFP's first filing, lists David Koch as by far the single largest contributor to its foundation, donating $850,000.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Money in Politics: The Companies Behind David Koch's Americans For Prosperity |first=Pema |last=Levy |date=September 24, 2013 |access-date=March 20, 2015 |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/money-politics-companies-behind-david-kochs-americans-prosperity-1410408 |work=[[International Business Times]] |quote=David Koch was the top contributor, providing $850,000.}}</ref> Koch said that he sympathized with the [[Tea Party movement]], but denied directly supporting it, having stated that: \"I've never been to a tea party event. No one representing the tea party has ever even approached me.\"<ref name=Wallet />\n\nKoch sat on the board of the libertarian [[Cato Institute]] and [[Reason Foundation]] and donated to both organizations.<ref name=\"Mayer\">{{Cite journal |url=https://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2010/08/30/100830fa_fact_mayer |title=Covert Operations: The billionaire brothers who are waging a war against Obama |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 30, 2010 |first=Jane |last=Mayer |authorlink=Jane Mayer}}</ref><ref name=Wallet /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125064719500442047 |title=Conservatives Take a Page From Left's Online Playbook |journal=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=August 20, 2009 |first=Jake |last=Sherman |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, [[Jane Mayer]] wrote an article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' on the political spending of David and Charles Koch. It stated: \"As their fortunes grew, Charles and David Koch became the primary underwriters of hard-line libertarian politics in America.\"<ref name=\"Mayer\" /> An opinion piece by journalist [[Yasha Levine]] in ''[[The New York Observer]]'' said Mayer's article had failed to mention that the Kochs' \"free market philanthropy belies the immense profit they have made from corporate welfare.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://observer.com/2010/09/7-ways-the-koch-bros-benefit-from-corporate-welfare/ |last=Levine |first=Yasha |authorlink=Yasha Levine|date=September 1, 2010| title=7 Ways the Koch Bros. Benefit from Corporate Welfare|work=[[The New York Observer]] |access-date=December 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine included Charles and David Koch among the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] of the year, for their involvement in supporting the [[Tea Party movement]] and the criticism they received from liberals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferguson|first=Andrew|title=The 2011 TIME 100|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2066367_2066369_2066324,00.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=April 22, 2011 |date=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==== Climate change denial ====\nAccording to an oped by Alex Kotch in ''The Guardian'', Koch was \"a key funder of [[climate change denial]]ism, stiff-arming scientists in order to further plunder the earth he was destroying.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kotch |first1=Alex |title=Death and destruction: this is David Koch's sad legacy {{!}} Alex Kotch |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/aug/27/death-destruction-david-koch-legacy |website=The Guardian |date=27 August 2019}}</ref> The Koch brothers' involvement in blocking climate change legislation dates back to 1991, when the Cato Institute held a conference called \"Global Environmental Crisis: Science or Politics?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/kochland-examines-how-the-koch-brothers-made-their-fortune-and-the-influence-it-bought|title=\"Kochland\" Examines the Koch Brothers\u2019 Early, Crucial Role in Climate-Change Denial|date=August 13, 2019|access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Prison reform ====\nIn July 2015, David and Charles Koch were commended by both President Obama and activist [[Van Jones|Anthony Van Jones]] for their bipartisan efforts to reform the prison system in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nelson|first=Colleen Mccain; Fields, Gary |title=Obama, Koch Brothers in Unlikely Alliance to Overhaul Criminal Justice|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 16, 2015 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-koch-brothers-in-unlikely-alliance-to-overhaul-criminal-justice-1437090737 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=wapos>{{Cite news|last=Horwitz|first=Sari|title=Unlikely Allies|work=The Washington Post|date=August 15, 2015 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sf/national/2015/08/15/clemency-the-issue-that-obama-and-the-koch-brothers-actually-agree-on/}}</ref> For nearly 10 years, the Kochs advocated for several reforms within the criminal justice system which include reducing recidivism rates, simplifying the employment process for the rehabilitated, and defending private property from government seizures through [[asset forfeiture]].<ref name=wapos /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cjonline.com/news/2015-10-15/forfeiture-reform-aligns-likes-billionaire-charles-koch-aclu |title=Forfeiture reform aligns likes of billionaire Charles Koch, ACLU|work=[[The Topeka Capital-Journal]] |date=October 15, 2015|first=Mary | last=Hudetz}}</ref> Allying with groups such as the [[ACLU]], the [[Center for American Progress]], [[Families Against Mandatory Minimums]], the [[Coalition for Public Safety]], and the [[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation|MacArthur Foundation]], the Kochs maintained that current prison system unfairly targeted low-income and minority communities at the expense of the public budget.<ref name=wapos /><ref name=rtody>{{Cite web|title=Koch brothers join Obama in advocating US prison reform|work=Russian Today|date=July 17, 2015|url=https://www.rt.com/usa/310128-koch-brothers-obama-prisons/}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nKoch established the [[Koch family foundations#David H. Koch Charitable Foundation|David H. Koch Charitable Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Koch Family Foundations|url=http://www.kochfamilyfoundations.org/FoundationsDHK.asp |title=David H. Koch Charitable Foundation and Personal Philanthropy|date=|access-date=November 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Levinthal|first1=Dan|title=The Koch brothers' foundation network explained|url=https://www.publicintegrity.org/2015/10/30/18713/koch-brothers-foundation-network-explained|publisher=The Center for Public Integrity|access-date=April 12, 2018|date=October 30, 2015}}</ref> Beginning in 2006, the [[Chronicle of Philanthropy]] listed Koch as one of the world's top 50 philanthropists.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|title=No. 45: David H. Koch |url=http://philanthropy.com/section/Philanthropy-50/370/ |publisher=The Chronicle of Philanthropy |access-date=October 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008194753/http://philanthropy.com/section/Philanthropy-50/370 |archivedate=October 8, 2011}}</ref> He sat on the Board of Trustees of [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]] from 1988 until his death in 2019.<ref name=NYP>{{Cite web|title=Hospital Leadership - Board of Trustees|url=http://nyp.org/about/board-trustees.html|publisher=New York Presbyterian|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Arts ===\nIn July 2008, Koch pledged $100&nbsp;million over 10 years to renovate the New York State Theater in the [[Lincoln Center|Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts]]; the Theater is the home of the New York City Ballet.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/10/arts/10linc.html |title=David H. Koch to Give 100 Million to Theater |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 10, 2008 |first=Robin |last=Pogrebin}}</ref> According to ''The New York Times'', Koch's gift was \"transformative, enabling a full-scale renovation of the stage\" that included \"an enlarged orchestra pit that mechanically rises\". The theater was renamed the [[David H. Koch Theater]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/arts/david-koch-arts-patron.html|title=David Koch, Embraced as an Arts Patron, Even as Criticism Grew|first1=Elizabeth A.|last1=Harris|first2=Robin|last2=Pogrebin|date=August 23, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Koch also pledged $10&nbsp;million to renovate fountains outside the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref name=Souccar>{{Cite news |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20100627/ANNIVERSARY/100619869/1072 |title=It's a Philanthropy Thing |work=Crain's New York Business |date=June 27, 2010 |first=Miriam Kreinin |last=Souccar}}</ref>\n\nKoch was a trustee of the [[American Ballet Theatre]] for 25 years<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.palmbeachdailynews.com/society/insider/american-ballet-theatre-celebrates-70th-season-david-kochs-723608.html |title=American Ballet Theatre Celebrates 70th Season, David Koch's Birthday |work=[[Palm Beach Daily News]] |date=June 2, 2010 |first=Shannon |last=Donnelly}}</ref> and contributed more than $6&nbsp;million to the theater.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-05-17/david-koch-toasted-by-michelle-obama-caroline-kennedy-at-n-y-ballet-gala.html |title=David Koch Toasted by Caroline Kennedy, Robert DeNiro |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=May 17, 2010 |first=Patrick |last=Cole}}</ref> He was also a member of the Board of Trustees of [[WGBH-TV]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wgbh.org/about/BoardofTrustees.cfm |title=Board of Trustees |publisher=WGBH|access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Cohan|first1=William|title=David Koch's Chilling Effect on Public Television |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2013-06-09/david-koch-s-chilling-effect-on-public-television |publisher=Bloomberg |access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nFrom 1982 to 2013, Koch contributed $18.6&nbsp;million to [[WGBH Educational Foundation]], including $10&nbsp;million to the [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS) show ''[[Nova (American TV program)|Nova]]''.<ref name=\"heraldwgbhkoch\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/local_coverage/2013/10/activists_put_heat_on_gbh_to_oust_donor_board_giant |date=October 4, 2013 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |last=Cassidy |first=Chris |title=Activists put heat on 'GBH to oust donor, board giant |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208052702/http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/local_coverage/2013/10/activists_put_heat_on_gbh_to_oust_donor_board_giant |archivedate=December 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/about/funders.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010185627/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/about/funders.html |url-status=live |date=October 10, 2018 |archive-date=October 10, 2018 |access-date=October 17, 2018 |title=Funders |publisher=[[WGBH-TV]] |quote=Funders for Season 44 include Draper, 23andMe, Cancer Treatment Centers of America, the '''David H. Koch Fund for Science''', the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, and PBS Stations. ... Funders for Season 40 include Boeing (episodes 4007, 4009-4015, 4017-4024), Lockheed Martin (episodes 4003-4005) Franklin Templeton (episodes 4007, 4009-4016) the '''David H. Koch Fund for Science''', the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, and PBS Stations.}}</ref> Koch was a contributor to the [[Smithsonian Institution]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], including a $20&nbsp;million gift to the [[American Museum of Natural History]], creating the David H. Koch Dinosaur Wing and a contribution of $15&nbsp;million to the [[National Museum of Natural History]] to create the new ''[[David H. Koch Hall of Human Origins]]'', which opened on the museum's 100th anniversary of its location on the National Mall on March 17, 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/gallery/2010/03/17/GA2010031702837.html |title=Smithsonian to Open Hall Dedicated to Story of Human Evolution |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 30, 2010 |first= |last=}}</ref> He also served on the executive board of the [[Institute of Human Origins]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=IHO Research Council and Executive Board|url=https://iho.asu.edu/people/iho-research-council |publisher=Institute of Human Origins|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419193708/https://iho.asu.edu/people/iho-research-council|archivedate=April 19, 2016}}</ref> In 2012, Koch contributed US$35&nbsp;million to the [[Smithsonian]] to build a new dinosaur exhibition hall at the [[National Museum of Natural History]].<ref name=dino$>{{Cite web |url=http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/smithsonian-s-national-museum-natural-history-build-new-dinosaur-hall |title=Smithsonian's National Museum of Natural History to Build New Dinosaur Hall &#124; Newsdesk |publisher=Newsdesk.si.edu |date=May 3, 2012 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = David Koch donates $35&nbsp;million to National Museum of Natural History for dinosaur hall|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/david-koch-donates-35-million-to-national-museum-of-natural-history-for-dinosaur-hall/2012/05/03/gIQAIjT3yT_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 3, 2012|access-date=January 24, 2016 |issn=0190-8286|first=Jacqueline|last=Trescott}}</ref>\n\nKoch was also a benefactor of the [[Deerfield Academy]], his alma mater. The Academy's natatorium, science center, and field house are named after him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.recorder.com/DA-alum-David-Koch-dies-27936537|title=DA alum David Koch dies|date=August 24, 2019|website=Greenfield Recorder}}</ref> Koch was named the Academy's first Lifetime Trustee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/08/30/covert-operations|title=The Koch Brothers\u2019 Covert Ops|first=Jane|last=Mayer|date=August 23, 2010|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref>\n\nKoch gave $10&nbsp;million to the [[Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Koch Brothers' Ten Most Shocking Power Grabs|url=http://thefederalist.com/2015/02/02/the-koch-brothers-ten-most-shocking-power-grabs/|access-date=February 14, 2016 |last=Media|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Medical research ===\nKoch said his biggest contributions go toward a \"moon shot\" campaign to finding the cure for cancer, according to his profile on [[Forbes]].<ref name=\"forbes\" /> Between 1998 and 2012, Koch contributed at least $395&nbsp;million to medical research causes and institutions.<ref name=PhilMag>{{Cite news|last=Sparks|first=Evan|title=The Team Builder |url=http://www.philanthropyroundtable.org/topic/excellence_in_philanthropy/the_team_builder|access-date=September 26, 2012 |newspaper=[[Philanthropy (magazine)|Philanthropy]]|date=Summer 2012}}</ref>\n\nKoch was a member of the board of directors of the [[Prostate Cancer Foundation]] and contributed $41&nbsp;million to the foundation, including $5&nbsp;million to a collaborative project in the field of [[nanotechnology]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pcf.org/site/c.leJRIROrEpH/b.5801629/k.8E55/David_H_Koch_8211_Prostate_Cancer_Foundation_NanoMedicine_Gift_Announced.htm |title=David H. Koch \u2013 Prostate Cancer Foundation Nano-Medicine Gift Announced |publisher=PCF.org |date=October 12, 2007 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Dolan|first1=Kerry|title=Warren Buffett Has Plenty of Company Among Powerful in Battling Prostate Cancer|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2012/04/17/warren-buffett-has-plenty-of-company-among-prostate-cancer-survivors/#66538e462c78|work=Forbes|access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> An eponym of the David H. Koch Chair of the Prostate Cancer Foundation, the position is held by [[Dr. Jonathan Simons]].<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Clinical Data for World's First Truly Non-Invasive Prostate Cancer Test Published in JAMA Oncology |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20160412005315/en/Clinical-Data-World%E2%80%99s-Non-Invasive-Prostate-Cancer-Test |publisher=Exosome Diagnostics|access-date=April 12, 2018|date=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Koch gave $20&nbsp;million to [[Johns Hopkins University]] [[Johns Hopkins School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] in [[Baltimore]] for cancer research. The building he financed was named the David H. Koch Cancer Research Building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/news/media/releases/david_koch_gives_20_million_for_hopkins_cancer_research|title=David Koch Gives $20 Million for Hopkins Cancer Research|publisher=hopkinsmedicine.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he contributed $100&nbsp;million to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology for the construction of a new {{Convert|350000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} research and technology facility to serve as the home of the [[David H. Koch Institute for Integrative Cancer Research]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kochfamilyfoundations.org/pdfs/Koch%2002-2008%20%20Spectrum%20EmpathyforOthers.pdf |format=PDF |title=Empathy For Others |publisher=Kochfamilyfoundations.org |access-date=June 10, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311202401/http://www.kochfamilyfoundations.org/pdfs/Koch%2002-2008%20%20Spectrum%20EmpathyforOthers.pdf |archive-date=March 11, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> From the time he joined the MIT Corporation in 1988, Koch gave at least $185&nbsp;million to MIT,<ref name=PhilMag /> $15&nbsp;million to [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]] [[Weill Cornell Medical College of Cornell University|Weill Cornell Medical Center]]<ref name=\"WSJ 20071009\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119189124817352914|title=Institutional Gift, With a Catch|first=Sally | last=Beatty |date=October 9, 2007|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url-access=subscription}}</ref> and $30&nbsp;million to the [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York City.<ref name=\"WSJ 20071009\" /> The same year, he donated $25&nbsp;million to the [[University of Texas M. D. Anderson Cancer Center]] in [[Houston]] to establish the David Koch Center for Applied Research in Genitourinary Cancers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Koch-gives-18-million-gift-to-M-D-Anderson-1800063.php|title=Koch gives $18 million gift to M.D. Anderson|date=2007-11-10|website=Houston Chronicle|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Koch gave $5&nbsp;million to the House Ear Institute, in Los Angeles, to create a center for hearing restoration,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> and $25&nbsp;million to the [[Hospital for Special Surgery]] in New York City<ref>{{Cite web|title=No. 45: David H. Koch|url=http://philanthropy.com/article/No-45-David-H-Koch/126132/|publisher=The Chronicle of Philanthropy|access-date=October 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joshfriedland.com/pdfs/HSS_DtoR_13_Fall_2007.pdf |format=PDF |title=Discovery to Recovery : Clinical and Research Highlights at HSS |date=2007 |publisher=Joshfriedland.com |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\nIn 2013, he gave $100&nbsp;million to [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]], the largest philanthropic donation in its history, beginning a $2&nbsp;billion campaign to conclude in 2019 for a new [[ambulatory care]] center and renovation the infrastructure of the hospital's five sites.<ref name=NYPresb>{{Cite web|last=NewYork-Presbyterian|title=NewYork-Presbyterian Announces $100 Million Donation from David H. Koch \u2013 Largest in Hospital's History \u2013 to Fund Outpatient Facility on Manhattan's East Side|url=http://nyp.org/news/hospital/David-Koch-Donation-2013.html|access-date=June 1, 2013|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he committed $150&nbsp;million to [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in [[New York City]] to build the David H. Koch Center for Cancer Care, which will be housed in a 23-story building in development between East 73rd and 74th Streets overlooking the [[FDR Drive]]. The center will combine state-of-the-art cancer treatment in an environment that supports patients, families, and caregivers. The building will include flexible personal and community spaces, educational offerings, and opportunities for physical exercise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mskcc.org/press-releases/msk-receives-gift-150-million-david-koch-patient-facility |title=Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center Receives Record Gift of $150&nbsp;million from David Koch for Innovative Patient Care Facility|access-date=May 20, 2015|date=May 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Wealth ==\nKoch was the fourth-richest person in the United States in 2012 and was the wealthiest resident of [[New York City]] in 2013.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{Cite news |agency=Forbes|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/david-koch|title=David Koch \u2013 Forbes |date=March 9, 2011 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> As of June 2019, Koch was ranked as the 11th-richest person in the world (tied with his brother Charles), with a fortune of $50.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/david-koch/ |title=David Koch |access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Fred with David and Julia Koch (1518448020).jpg|thumb|Fred Thompson poses with David Koch and his wife Julia.]]\nKoch married Julia Flesher in 1996.<ref name=\"Woman Ascending\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/11/magazine/woman-ascending-a-marble-staircase.html?pagewanted=all |title=Woman Ascending A Marble Staircase |first=Elizabeth | last=Bumiller |work=The New York Times |date=January 11, 1998 |access-date=August 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"weddings\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/26/style/weddings-julia-m-flesher-david-h-koch.html |title=Weddings: Julia M. Flesher, David H. Koch |work=The New York Times |date=May 26, 1996 |access-date=September 2, 2010}}</ref> They had three children.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=McFadden |first1=Robert D. |title=David Koch, Billionaire Who Fueled Right-Wing Movement, Dies at 79 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/us/david-koch-dead.html |access-date=August 24, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1991, Koch was a passenger on board [[US Airways|USAir]] Flight 1493 when it [[Los Angeles runway disaster|collided with another aircraft]] on a runway at [[Los Angeles International Airport]], killing 35 people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/03/07/opinion/last-in-line-for-the-exit.html|title='Last in Line for the Exit'|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1991-03-07}}</ref> Koch survived and said in an interview in 2014 that it helped change his life and prompted him to become \"tremendously philanthropic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/video/david-koch-plane-crash-helped-change-life-27598921|title=David Koch on the Plane Crash That Helped Change His Life|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=2014-12-15}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]]' death in 1994, Koch purchased her 15-room apartment at [[1040 Fifth Avenue]] and in 2006 resold it to billionaire [[Glenn Dubin]]. Koch then moved to Onassis's childhood NYC home, [[740 Park Avenue]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2006/06/jackie-flat-gets-32-m-2/|title=Jackie Flat Gets $32 M.|date=June 26, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Koch was diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]]. He underwent radiation, surgery, and hormone therapy, but the cancer repeatedly returned. Koch said he believed his experience with cancer encouraged him to fund medical research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/08/david-koch-cause-of-death-cancer/|title=David Koch\u2019s Cause of Death: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|first=Alyssa|last=Choiniere|date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKoch died at his home in [[Southampton, New York]], on August 23, 2019, at the age of 79.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/us/david-koch-dead.html|title= David Koch, Billionaire Who Fueled Right-Wing Movement, Dies at 79|work = [[The New York Times]]|date = August 23, 2019|access-date = August 23, 2019|last = McFadden|first = Robert D.|authorlink = Robert D. McFadden}}</ref> Koch's wife, Julia Koch, and their three children inherited a 42% stake in Koch Industries from Koch upon his death.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/julia-koch/?list=forbes-400#2fab53562b9c|title=Julia Koch & family|access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Koch family]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{C-SPAN|davidkoch}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101103024037/http://www.influenceexplorer.com/individual/koch-david/741672ab1e0a4314be416ce3cfc2afbc Political contributions] from ''Influence Explorer'' at the [[Sunlight Foundation]]\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/press/ReportView.phtml?r=434 Names in the News: David and Charles Koch] at FollowTheMoney.org\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/k/david_h_koch Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/sonsofwichitahow0000schu|first=Daniel|last=Schulman|title=Sons of Wichita|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=978-1455518739|date=May 20, 2014|url-access=registration}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[David Bergland]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] [[List of United States Libertarian Party presidential tickets|nominee]] for [[Vice President of the United States]]|years=[[1980 United States presidential election|1980]]}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[James A. Lewis|Jim Lewis]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Libertarian Party (United States)}}\n{{1980 United States presidential election}}\n{{Koch family}}\n{{Koch Industries}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koch, David}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:1980 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American political fundraisers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kansas]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Cato Institute people]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deerfield Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Drug policy reform activists]]\n[[Category:Engineers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Koch family|David Koch]]\n[[Category:Libertarian Party (United States) vice presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:MIT Engineers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Libertarians]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Wichita, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Wichita, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Survivors of aviation accidents or incidents]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the American businessman||}}\n{{short description|American billionaire heir and businessman}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = David Koch\n| image       = David Koch by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption     = Koch in 2015\n| birth_name  = David Hamilton Koch\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1940|5|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Wichita, Kansas]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2019|8|23|1940|5|3}}\n| death_place = [[Southampton, New York]], U.S.\n| education   = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Bachelor of Science|SB]], [[Master of Science|SM]])\n| occupation  = Vice president of [[Koch Industries]]\n| known_for   = Philanthropy to cultural and medical institutions<br />Support of libertarian and conservative causes<ref name=\"Mayer\" /><ref name=\"Wallet\">{{Cite news |url=https://nymag.com/news/features/67285/ |title=The Billionaire's Party: David Koch is New York's second-richest man, a celebrated patron of the arts, and the tea party's wallet |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=July 25, 2010 |first=Andrew |last=Goldman |access-date=August 26, 2010}}</ref>\n| party       = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] (before 1984)<br />[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (1984\u20132019)\n| boards      = [[Aspen Institute]], [[Cato Institute]], [[Reason Foundation]], [[Americans for Prosperity|Americans for Prosperity Foundation]], [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]], [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History]], [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], [[American Ballet Theatre]], [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]], [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]], [[American Museum of Natural History]]\n| spouse      = {{Marriage|Julia Flesher Koch|1996}}\n| children    = 3\n| parents     = [[Fred C. Koch]]<br />Mary Robinson\n| relatives   = [[Frederick R. Koch]] (brother)<br />[[Charles Koch]] (brother)<br />[[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill Koch]] (twin brother)\n| networth    = [[United States dollar|US$]]48&nbsp;billion (June 2019)\n}}\n\n'''David Hamilton Koch''' ({{IPAc-en|k|o\u028a|k}}; May 3, 1940&nbsp;\u2013 August 23, 2019) was an American businessman, philanthropist, political activist, and chemical engineer. In 1970, he joined the family business: [[Koch Industries]], the second-largest privately held company in the United States. He became president of the subsidiary Koch Engineering in 1979, and became a co-owner of Koch Industries (along with elder brother [[Charles Koch|Charles]]) in 1983. Koch served as an executive vice president of Koch Industries until he retired due to health issues in 2018.\n\nKoch was a [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]]. He was the 1980 [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] candidate for [[Vice President of the United States]] and helped finance the campaign. He founded [[Citizens for a Sound Economy]] and donated to advocacy groups and [[Political activities of the Koch brothers|political campaigns]], most of which were [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. Koch became a Republican in 1984; in 2012, he spent over $100&nbsp;million to oppose the re-election of President [[Barack Obama]].\n\nKoch was the fourth-richest person in the United States in 2012 and was the wealthiest resident of [[New York City]] in 2013. As of June 2019, Koch was ranked as the 11th-richest person in the world (tied with his brother Charles), with a fortune of $50.5&nbsp;billion. Known for his philanthropy, Koch contributed to the [[Lincoln Center]], [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center|Sloan Kettering]], [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]], and the Dinosaur Wing at the [[American Museum of Natural History]]. The New York State Theater at Lincoln Center, home of the [[New York City Ballet]], was renamed the [[David H. Koch Theater]] in 2008 following Koch's gift of $100&nbsp;million for the renovation of the theater.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKoch was born in [[Wichita, Kansas]], the son of Mary Clementine (n\u00e9e Robinson) and [[Fred C. Koch|Fred Chase Koch]], a chemical engineer. David's paternal grandfather, [[Harry Koch (businessman)|Harry Koch]], was a Dutch immigrant who founded the ''Quanah Tribune-Chief'' newspaper and was a founding shareholder of the [[Quanah, Acme and Pacific Railway]].<ref name=\"new netherland\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nnp.org/nni/Publications/Dutch-American/kochd.htm |title=Koch, David Hamilton (1940) |publisher=New Netherland Project |access-date=August 31, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819225843/http://www.nnp.org/nni/Publications/Dutch-American/kochd.htm |archive-date=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> David was the third of four sons, with elder brothers [[Frederick R. Koch|Frederick]], Charles, and nineteen-minute-younger twin<ref name=\"kochbtp\" /> [[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill]]. His maternal ancestors included [[William Ingraham Kip]], an Episcopal bishop; [[William Burnet Kinney]], a politician; and [[Elizabeth Clementine Stedman]], a writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.palmbeachdailynews.com/obituaries/20190824/palm-beach-obituary-bill-koch-remembers-brother-david-as-rsquooutstanding-human-best-friendrsquo|title=Palm Beach obituary: Bill Koch remembers brother David as 'outstanding human, best friend'|first=Shannon|last=Donnelly|website=Palm Beach Daily News}}</ref>\n\nKoch attended the [[Deerfield Academy]] prep school in Massachusetts, graduating in 1959. He attended [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), earning both a [[bachelor's degree|bachelor's]] (1962) and a [[master's degree]] (1963) in [[chemical engineering]]. He was a member of the [[Beta Theta Pi]] fraternity. Koch played basketball at MIT, averaging 21 points per game at MIT over three years, a school record. He also held the single-game scoring record of 41 points from 1962 until 2009, when it was eclipsed by [[Jimmy Bartolotta]].<ref name=\"kochbtp\">{{Cite journal |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/114135/david-and-william-koch-mit-basketball-players |title=David and William Koch as MIT Basketball Players |journal=The New Republic |date=August 14, 2013 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career at Koch Industries ==\nIn 1970, Koch joined [[Koch Industries]] under his brother [[Charles Koch|Charles]], to work as a technical-services manager. He founded the company's New York City office and in 1979 he became the president of his own division, Koch Engineering, renamed Chemical Technology Group. David's brothers [[Frederick R. Koch|Frederick]] and [[Bill Koch (businessman)|Bill]] had inherited stock in Koch Industries. In June 1983, after a bitter legal and boardroom battle, the stakes of Frederick and Bill were bought out for $1.1&nbsp;billion and Charles Koch and David Koch became majority owners in the company.<ref>{{Cite news | url= https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/28/business/brother-versus-brother-koch-family-s-long-legal-feud-is-headed-for-a-jury.html | title=Brother Versus Brother; Koch Family's Long Legal Feud Is Headed for a Jury | first=Leslie | last= Wayne | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 28, 1998 | url-status=live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180326160300/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/28/business/brother-versus-brother-koch-family-s-long-legal-feud-is-headed-for-a-jury.html | archivedate=March 26, 2018 | df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=MorningSun>\"Koch's wife granted order of restraint\". Pittsburg (KS) ''Morning Sun'', July 21, 2000.</ref> Legal disputes against Charles and David lasted roughly two decades. Frederick and Bill sided with [[J. Howard Marshall III]], [[J. Howard Marshall II]]'s eldest son, against Charles and David at one point, in order to take over the company. In 2001, Bill reached a settlement in a lawsuit where he had charged the company was taking oil from federal and Indian land; that settlement ended all litigation between the brothers.<ref name=WallStreet>\"Judge Clears Koch Brothers' Settlement Pact\". ''Wall Street Journal'', May 29, 2001.</ref> CBS News reported that Koch Industries settled for $25&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/11/27/60II/main252545.shtml |title=Blood And Oil |publisher=CBS News |date=2000-11-27 |access-date=2015-10-15}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2010, David Koch owned 42 percent of Koch Industries, as did his brother Charles.<ref name=Wallet /> He held four U.S patents.<ref name=\"TimeObit\">{{Cite news |url=https://time.com/5660040/david-koch-legacy/ |title=David Koch's Millions Remade the Republican Party. He Didn't Like the Results |work=Time |date=August 23, 2019 |first=Philip | last=Elliott}}</ref> Koch served as an executive vice president of Koch Industries until retiring due to health issues in 2018.<ref name=\"asgbio\">http://www.theadvocates.org/celebrities/david-koch.html {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070226111813/http://www.theadvocates.org/celebrities/david-koch.html|date=February 26, 2007}}</ref> His retirement was announced on June 5, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/06/05/david-koch-is-leaving-koch-industries-stepping-down-from-americans-for-prosperity/ |title=David Koch is leaving Koch Industries, stepping down from Americans for Prosperity |first=James |last=Hohmann |date=June 5, 2018 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=June 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political involvement ==\n{{See also|Political activities of the Koch brothers}}\n\n===Campaigns===\nKoch was the [[United States Libertarian Party|Libertarian Party]]'s [[Vice President of the United States|vice-presidential]] candidate in the [[1980 United States presidential election|1980 presidential election]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=Man Without a Candidate |authorlink=Charlotte Curtis |first=Charlotte |last=Curtis |date=October 16, 1984 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/16/arts/man-without-a-candidate.html |access-date=July 18, 2015}}</ref> sharing the party ticket with [[President of the United States|presidential]] candidate [[Ed Clark]]. The Clark\u2013Koch [[Ticket (election)|ticket]] promised to abolish [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], the [[Federal Reserve Board]], [[welfare]], [[minimum-wage]] laws, corporate taxes, all price supports and subsidies for agriculture and business, and [[U.S. Federal agencies]] including the SEC, EPA, ICC, FTC, OSHA, FBI, CIA, and DOE.<ref name=\"Mayer\" /><ref name=Buck>Rinker Buck, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ueUCAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA18&dq=David%20Koch&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q=David%20Koch&f=false \"How Those Libertarians Pay the Bills\"], [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]], November 3, 1980</ref> The ticket received 921,128 votes, 1% of the total nationwide vote,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1980&off=0&f=1|title=1980 Presidential General Election Results|first=David | last=Leip |publisher=uselectionatlas.org}}</ref> the Libertarian Party national ticket's best showing until [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] in terms of percentage and its best showing in terms of raw votes until the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 presidential election]], although that number was surpassed again in 2016.<ref name=Bennett>James T. Bennett, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eImBSPX63D0C&pg=PA167&dq=ed+clark+highest+vote+total+1980&hl=en&ei=YZB9TMd3goHyBufjrZkH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=ed%20clark%20highest%20vote%20total%201980&f=false ''Not Invited to the Party: How the Demopublicans Have Rigged the System and Left Independents Out in the Cold''], Springer, 2009, p. 167, {{ISBN|1-4419-0365-8}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Quixotic '80 Campaign Gave Birth to Kochs' Powerful Network |authorlink=Nicholas Confessore |first=Nicholas |last=Confessore |date=May 17, 2014 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/18/us/politics/quixotic-80-campaign-gave-birth-to-kochs-powerful-network.html |access-date=July 18, 2015 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> \"Compared to what [the Libertarians had] gotten before,\" Charles said, \"and where we were as a movement or as a political/ideological point of view, that was pretty remarkable, to get 1 percent of the vote.\"<ref name=Continetti>{{Cite news|first=Matthew |last=Continetti|authorlink=Matthew Continetti|title=The Paranoid Style in Liberal Politics|work=[[The Weekly Standard]]|date=April 4, 2011|url=https://www.weeklystandard.com/matthew-continetti/the-paranoid-style-in-liberal-politics}}</ref>\n\nAfter the bid, according to journalist [[Brian Doherty (journalist)|Brian Doherty]]'s ''[[Radicals for Capitalism]]'', Koch viewed politicians as \"actors playing out a script.\"<ref name=Mayer /><ref name=\"Doherty2008\">{{Cite book|last=Doherty|first=Brian |authorlink=Brian Doherty (journalist)|title=Radicals for Capitalism: A Freewheeling History of the Modern American Libertarian Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6g_NGAAACAAJ|access-date=October 10, 2011|date=May 26, 2008|publisher=Perseus Books Group|isbn=978-1-58648-572-6|page=410}}</ref>\n\nKoch credited the 1976 presidential campaign of [[Roger MacBride]] as his inspiration for getting involved in politics:\n\n<blockquote style=font-size:100%>Here was a great guy, advocating all the things I believed in. He wanted less government and taxes, and was talking about repealing all these victimless crime laws that accumulated on the books. I have friends who smoke pot. I know many homosexuals. It's ridiculous to treat them as criminals&nbsp;\u2014 and here was someone running for president, saying just that.<ref name=Buck /></blockquote>\n\nKoch gave his own vice presidential campaign $100,000 a month after being chosen as [[Ed Clark]]'s running mate. \"We'd like to abolish the [[Federal Elections Commission]] and all the limits on campaign spending anyway,\" Koch said in 1980. When asked why he ran, he replied: \"Lord knows I didn't need a job, but I believe in what the Libertarians are saying. I suppose if they hadn't come along, I could have been a big Republican from [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]]. But hell&nbsp;\u2014 ''everybody'' from Kansas is a Republican.\"<ref name=Buck />\n\nIn 1984, Koch broke with the Libertarian Party when it supported eliminating all taxes. Subsequently, Koch was a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].<ref name=Wallet />{{Rp|4}} Koch donated  \nto various [[Political activities of the Koch brothers|political campaigns]], most of which were [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/orgs/summary.php?id=D000000186&cycle=A |title=Koch Industries: Summary |publisher=OpenSecrets.org |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> In February 2012, during the [[Wisconsin gubernatorial recall election]], Koch said of Wisconsin governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], \"We're helping him, as we should. We've gotten pretty good at this over the years. We've spent a lot of money in Wisconsin. We're going to spend more,\" and said that by \"we\" he meant Americans for Prosperity.<ref>{{Cite news |title=David Koch intends to cure cancer in his lifetime and remake American politics |date=February 20, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]] |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/business/david-koch-intends-to-cure-cancer-in-his-lifetime-/nL4Fb/ |first=Stacey |last=Singer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |magazine=[[The Nation]] |authorlink=John Nichols (journalist) |first=John |last=Nichols |title=Scott Walker's Koch Connection Goes Bad |date=February 24, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/166450/scott-walkers-koch-connection-goes-bad}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Billionaire Koch brothers gave $8&nbsp;million to Wisconsin Gov. Scott Walker recall campaign, Dem chair says |first=Tom |last=Kertscher |date=June 20, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |url=http://www.politifact.com/wisconsin/statements/2012/jun/20/debbie-wasserman-schultz/billionaire-koch-brothers-gave-8-million-wisconsin/ |publisher=[[PolitiFact]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |magazine=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |title=How Did Wisconsin Become the Most Politically Divisive Place in America? |first=Dan |last=Kaufman |date=May 24, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/27/magazine/how-did-wisconsin-become-the-most-politically-divisive-place-in-america.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=On Politics: David Koch: 'We've spent a lot of money in Wisconsin. We're going to spend more.' |date=February 20, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2015 |first=Mary |last=Spicuzza |newspaper=[[Wisconsin State Journal]] |url=http://host.madison.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/on-politics/on-politics-david-koch-we-ve-spent-a-lot-of/article_dc909fe4-5bde-11e1-a0db-0019bb2963f4.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Koch spent over $100&nbsp;million to oppose the re-election of President [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/15/us/politics/122-million-in-2012-spending-by-koch-group.html |title=$122 Million in 2012 Spending by Koch Group |last=Confessore |first=Nicholas |date=2013-11-14 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2019-08-25 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tariniparti/billionaire-david-koch-dies |title=Billionaire David Koch, Who Shaped Modern Conservative Politics, Has Died |access-date=2019-08-25 |publisher=[[BuzzFeed News]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Views ===\nKoch supported policies that promote [[individual liberty]] and [[free market]] principles, and supported reducing government spending.<ref name=\"kochnyt\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/05/us/05koch.html|date=March 5, 2011 |work=The New York Times|title=Cancer Research Before Activism, Billionaire Conservative Donor Says|last=Cooper|first=Michael}}</ref><ref>The Koch Brothers December 24, 2012 p. 96 Forbes</ref> Koch supported a [[non-interventionist]] foreign policy; \"Pursuing a very aggressive foreign policy,\" he said, \"is an extremely expensive endeavor for the U.S. government. The cost of maintaining a huge military force abroad is gigantic. It's so big it puts a severe strain on the U.S. economy, creating economic hardships here at home.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://reason.com/archives/1987/02/01/the-new-antiwar-capitalists/print|title=The New Antiwar Capitalists|website=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref> Koch opposed the [[Iraq War]], saying that the war has \"cost a lot of money and it's taken so many American lives\", and \"I question whether that was the right thing to do. In hindsight that looks like it was not a good policy.\"<ref name=Continetti /> In an impromptu interview with the blog ThinkProgress, he was quoted as saying he would like the new, 2011 Republican Congress to \"cut the hell out of spending, balance the budget, reduce regulations, and support business.\"<ref name=\"kochtp\">{{Cite news |url=http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2011/01/06/137586/koch-teaparty-us/|publisher=ThinkProgress|date=January 6, 2011|last=Fang |first=Lee|title=Exclusive: Polluter Billionaire David Koch Says Tea Party 'Rank And File Are Just Normal People Like Us'}}</ref> He was against the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and the Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act.<ref name=\"Wallet\" /> He was skeptical about anthropogenic [[global warming]]. He said a warmer planet would be good, because \"Earth will be able to support enormously more people, because a far greater land area will be available to produce food\".<ref name=\"Wallet\" /> Koch considered himself a [[Cultural liberalism|social liberal]]<ref name=\"Bell\">{{Cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2014/12/billionaire-david-koch-says-hes-a-social-liberal/ |title=Billionaire David Koch Says He's a Social Liberal|publisher=ABC News|date=December 14, 2014|access-date=December 29, 2014|first=Benjamin | last=Bell}}</ref> who supported women's [[right to choose]],<ref name=\"Fischer\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/14/politics/david-koch-gay-rights-abortion-democrats/ |title=David Koch is pro-choice, supports gay rights; just not Democrats|publisher=CNN|date=December 15, 2014 |access-date=December 29, 2014|first=Sara | last=Fischer}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]], [[same-sex marriage]] and [[stem-cell research]].<ref name=\"Wallet\" /><ref>Joseph Patrick McCormick, [http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/09/02/billionaire-gop-supporter-disagrees-with-platform-says-he-supports-gay-marriage/ Billionaire GOP supporter disagrees with platform, says he supports gay marriage], ''[[PinkNews]]'', September 2, 2012</ref> He opposed the [[war on drugs]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coaston |first1=Jane |title=\"David Koch walked the walk\": a libertarian on the Koch brother\u2019s legacy |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/8/23/20829962/david-koch-libertarian-legacy |publisher=Vox |accessdate=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nKoch opposed several of President [[Barack Obama|Barack Obama's]] policies. An article from the ''[[Weekly Standard]]'', detailing the \"left's obsession\" with the Koch brothers, quotes Koch stating that Obama is \"the most radical president we've ever had as a nation ... and has done more damage to the free enterprise system and long-term prosperity than any president we've ever had.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/articles/paranoid-style-liberal-politics_555525.html?nopager=1|title=The Paranoid Style in Liberal Politics|work=[[The Weekly Standard]]}}</ref> Koch said that Obama's father's economic [[socialism]], practiced in [[Kenya]], explains why Obama has \"sort of antibusiness and anti-free enterprise\" influences.<ref name=Continetti /> Koch said that Obama is \"scary\", a \"hardcore socialist\" who is \"marvelous at pretending to be something other than that.\"<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite news |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intel/2011/05/billionaire_conservative_david.html|title=David Koch Gives President Obama Zero Credit for Bin Laden's Death|work=New York|first=Sarah|last=Owen|date=May 5, 2011}}</ref> Koch contributed almost entirely to Republican candidates in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/11/charts-map-koch-brothers-2012-spending|title=Charts: How Much Have the Kochs Spent on the 2012 Election?|work=Mother Jones}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nKoch donated funds to various advocacy groups.<ref name=\"Wallet\" /> In 1984, he founded [[Citizens for a Sound Economy]] (CSE).<ref name=Mazur>Suzan Mazur, [https://books.google.com/books?id=wk2FfQQ_DmsC&pg=PA244 \"The Altenberg 16: An Expos\u00e9 of the Evolution Industry\"], ''North Atlantic Books'', 2010, 343 pages</ref> He served as its Chairman of the [[board of directors]] and donated funds to it. [[Richard H. Fink]] served as its first president.<ref name=Continetti /> Koch was the chairman of the board and gave initial funding to the [[Americans for Prosperity|Americans for Prosperity Foundation]] and to a related advocacy organization, [[Americans for Prosperity]]. A Koch Industries spokesperson issued a press release stating \"No funding has been provided by Koch companies, the Koch foundations, or Charles Koch or David Koch specifically to support the tea parties.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/08/30/covert-operations|title=Covert Operations|first=Jane | last=Mayer |date=August 30, 2010 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref><ref name=\"WeigelFW\">{{Cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/04/dick_armey_please_koch_keep_di.html |first=David | last=Weigel |title=Dick Armey: Please, Koch, keep distancing yourself from me |work=The Washington Post |date=April 15, 2010}}</ref> Koch was the top initial funder of the Americans for Prosperity Foundation at $850,000.<ref>{{Cite news |title=David Koch Seeded Major Tea-Party Group, Private Donor List Reveals |first=Alex |last=Seitz-Wald |date=September 24, 2013 |access-date=March 20, 2015 |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/politics/david-koch-seeded-major-tea-party-group-private-donor-list-reveals-20130924 |work=[[National Journal]] |quote=But a donor list filed with the IRS labeled \"not open for public inspection\" from 2003, the year of AFP's first filing, lists David Koch as by far the single largest contributor to its foundation, donating $850,000.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Money in Politics: The Companies Behind David Koch's Americans For Prosperity |first=Pema |last=Levy |date=September 24, 2013 |access-date=March 20, 2015 |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/money-politics-companies-behind-david-kochs-americans-prosperity-1410408 |work=[[International Business Times]] |quote=David Koch was the top contributor, providing $850,000.}}</ref> Koch said that he sympathized with the [[Tea Party movement]], but denied directly supporting it, having stated that: \"I've never been to a tea party event. No one representing the tea party has ever even approached me.\"<ref name=Wallet />\n\nKoch sat on the board of the libertarian [[Cato Institute]] and [[Reason Foundation]] and donated to both organizations.<ref name=\"Mayer\">{{Cite journal |url=https://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2010/08/30/100830fa_fact_mayer |title=Covert Operations: The billionaire brothers who are waging a war against Obama |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |date=August 30, 2010 |first=Jane |last=Mayer |authorlink=Jane Mayer}}</ref><ref name=Wallet /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125064719500442047 |title=Conservatives Take a Page From Left's Online Playbook |journal=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=August 20, 2009 |first=Jake |last=Sherman |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, [[Jane Mayer]] wrote an article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' on the political spending of David and Charles Koch. It stated: \"As their fortunes grew, Charles and David Koch became the primary underwriters of hard-line libertarian politics in America.\"<ref name=\"Mayer\" /> An opinion piece by journalist [[Yasha Levine]] in ''[[The New York Observer]]'' said Mayer's article had failed to mention that the Kochs' \"free market philanthropy belies the immense profit they have made from corporate welfare.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://observer.com/2010/09/7-ways-the-koch-bros-benefit-from-corporate-welfare/ |last=Levine |first=Yasha |authorlink=Yasha Levine|date=September 1, 2010| title=7 Ways the Koch Bros. Benefit from Corporate Welfare|work=[[The New York Observer]] |access-date=December 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine included Charles and David Koch among the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] of the year, for their involvement in supporting the [[Tea Party movement]] and the criticism they received from liberals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferguson|first=Andrew|title=The 2011 TIME 100|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2066367_2066369_2066324,00.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=April 22, 2011 |date=April 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==== Climate change denial ====\nAccording to an oped by Alex Kotch in ''The Guardian'', Koch was \"a key funder of [[climate change denial]]ism, stiff-arming scientists in order to further plunder the earth he was destroying.\"ref>{{cite web |last1=Kotch |first1=Alex |title=Death and destruction: this is David Koch's sad legacy {{!}} Alex Kotch |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/aug/27/death-destruction-david-koch-legacy |website=The Guardian |date=27 August 2019}}</ref> The Koch brothers' involvement in blocking climate change legislation dates back to 1991, when the Cato Institute held a conference called \"Global Environmental Crisis: Science or Politics?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/kochland-examines-how-the-koch-brothers-made-their-fortune-and-the-influence-it-bought|title=\"Kochland\" Examines the Koch Brothers\u2019 Early, Crucial Role in Climate-Change Denial|date=August 13, 2019|access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Prison reform ====\nIn July 2015, David and Charles Koch were commended by both President Obama and activist [[Van Jones|Anthony Van Jones]] for their bipartisan efforts to reform the prison system in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nelson|first=Colleen Mccain; Fields, Gary |title=Obama, Koch Brothers in Unlikely Alliance to Overhaul Criminal Justice|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 16, 2015 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-koch-brothers-in-unlikely-alliance-to-overhaul-criminal-justice-1437090737 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=wapos>{{Cite news|last=Horwitz|first=Sari|title=Unlikely Allies|work=The Washington Post|date=August 15, 2015 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sf/national/2015/08/15/clemency-the-issue-that-obama-and-the-koch-brothers-actually-agree-on/}}</ref> For nearly 10 years, the Kochs advocated for several reforms within the criminal justice system which include reducing recidivism rates, simplifying the employment process for the rehabilitated, and defending private property from government seizures through [[asset forfeiture]].<ref name=wapos /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cjonline.com/news/2015-10-15/forfeiture-reform-aligns-likes-billionaire-charles-koch-aclu |title=Forfeiture reform aligns likes of billionaire Charles Koch, ACLU|work=[[The Topeka Capital-Journal]] |date=October 15, 2015|first=Mary | last=Hudetz}}</ref> Allying with groups such as the [[ACLU]], the [[Center for American Progress]], [[Families Against Mandatory Minimums]], the [[Coalition for Public Safety]], and the [[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation|MacArthur Foundation]], the Kochs maintained that current prison system unfairly targeted low-income and minority communities at the expense of the public budget.<ref name=wapos /><ref name=rtody>{{Cite web|title=Koch brothers join Obama in advocating US prison reform|work=Russian Today|date=July 17, 2015|url=https://www.rt.com/usa/310128-koch-brothers-obama-prisons/}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nKoch established the [[Koch family foundations#David H. Koch Charitable Foundation|David H. Koch Charitable Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Koch Family Foundations|url=http://www.kochfamilyfoundations.org/FoundationsDHK.asp |title=David H. Koch Charitable Foundation and Personal Philanthropy|date=|access-date=November 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Levinthal|first1=Dan|title=The Koch brothers' foundation network explained|url=https://www.publicintegrity.org/2015/10/30/18713/koch-brothers-foundation-network-explained|publisher=The Center for Public Integrity|access-date=April 12, 2018|date=October 30, 2015}}</ref> Beginning in 2006, the [[Chronicle of Philanthropy]] listed Koch as one of the world's top 50 philanthropists.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|title=No. 45: David H. Koch |url=http://philanthropy.com/section/Philanthropy-50/370/ |publisher=The Chronicle of Philanthropy |access-date=October 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008194753/http://philanthropy.com/section/Philanthropy-50/370 |archivedate=October 8, 2011}}</ref> He sat on the Board of Trustees of [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]] from 1988 until his death in 2019.<ref name=NYP>{{Cite web|title=Hospital Leadership - Board of Trustees|url=http://nyp.org/about/board-trustees.html|publisher=New York Presbyterian|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Arts ===\nIn July 2008, Koch pledged $100&nbsp;million over 10 years to renovate the New York State Theater in the [[Lincoln Center|Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts]]; the Theater is the home of the New York City Ballet.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/10/arts/10linc.html |title=David H. Koch to Give 100 Million to Theater |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 10, 2008 |first=Robin |last=Pogrebin}}</ref> According to ''The New York Times'', Koch's gift was \"transformative, enabling a full-scale renovation of the stage\" that included \"an enlarged orchestra pit that mechanically rises\". The theater was renamed the [[David H. Koch Theater]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/arts/david-koch-arts-patron.html|title=David Koch, Embraced as an Arts Patron, Even as Criticism Grew|first1=Elizabeth A.|last1=Harris|first2=Robin|last2=Pogrebin|date=August 23, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Koch also pledged $10&nbsp;million to renovate fountains outside the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref name=Souccar>{{Cite news |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20100627/ANNIVERSARY/100619869/1072 |title=It's a Philanthropy Thing |work=Crain's New York Business |date=June 27, 2010 |first=Miriam Kreinin |last=Souccar}}</ref>\n\nKoch was a trustee of the [[American Ballet Theatre]] for 25 years<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.palmbeachdailynews.com/society/insider/american-ballet-theatre-celebrates-70th-season-david-kochs-723608.html |title=American Ballet Theatre Celebrates 70th Season, David Koch's Birthday |work=[[Palm Beach Daily News]] |date=June 2, 2010 |first=Shannon |last=Donnelly}}</ref> and contributed more than $6&nbsp;million to the theater.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-05-17/david-koch-toasted-by-michelle-obama-caroline-kennedy-at-n-y-ballet-gala.html |title=David Koch Toasted by Caroline Kennedy, Robert DeNiro |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=May 17, 2010 |first=Patrick |last=Cole}}</ref> He was also a member of the Board of Trustees of [[WGBH-TV]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wgbh.org/about/BoardofTrustees.cfm |title=Board of Trustees |publisher=WGBH|access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Cohan|first1=William|title=David Koch's Chilling Effect on Public Television |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2013-06-09/david-koch-s-chilling-effect-on-public-television |publisher=Bloomberg |access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nFrom 1982 to 2013, Koch contributed $18.6&nbsp;million to [[WGBH Educational Foundation]], including $10&nbsp;million to the [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS) show ''[[Nova (American TV program)|Nova]]''.<ref name=\"heraldwgbhkoch\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/local_coverage/2013/10/activists_put_heat_on_gbh_to_oust_donor_board_giant |date=October 4, 2013 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |last=Cassidy |first=Chris |title=Activists put heat on 'GBH to oust donor, board giant |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208052702/http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/local_coverage/2013/10/activists_put_heat_on_gbh_to_oust_donor_board_giant |archivedate=December 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/about/funders.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010185627/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/about/funders.html |url-status=live |date=October 10, 2018 |archive-date=October 10, 2018 |access-date=October 17, 2018 |title=Funders |publisher=[[WGBH-TV]] |quote=Funders for Season 44 include Draper, 23andMe, Cancer Treatment Centers of America, the '''David H. Koch Fund for Science''', the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, and PBS Stations. ... Funders for Season 40 include Boeing (episodes 4007, 4009-4015, 4017-4024), Lockheed Martin (episodes 4003-4005) Franklin Templeton (episodes 4007, 4009-4016) the '''David H. Koch Fund for Science''', the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, and PBS Stations.}}</ref> Koch was a contributor to the [[Smithsonian Institution]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], including a $20&nbsp;million gift to the [[American Museum of Natural History]], creating the David H. Koch Dinosaur Wing and a contribution of $15&nbsp;million to the [[National Museum of Natural History]] to create the new ''[[David H. Koch Hall of Human Origins]]'', which opened on the museum's 100th anniversary of its location on the National Mall on March 17, 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/gallery/2010/03/17/GA2010031702837.html |title=Smithsonian to Open Hall Dedicated to Story of Human Evolution |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 30, 2010 |first= |last=}}</ref> He also served on the executive board of the [[Institute of Human Origins]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=IHO Research Council and Executive Board|url=https://iho.asu.edu/people/iho-research-council |publisher=Institute of Human Origins|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419193708/https://iho.asu.edu/people/iho-research-council|archivedate=April 19, 2016}}</ref> In 2012, Koch contributed US$35&nbsp;million to the [[Smithsonian]] to build a new dinosaur exhibition hall at the [[National Museum of Natural History]].<ref name=dino$>{{Cite web |url=http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/smithsonian-s-national-museum-natural-history-build-new-dinosaur-hall |title=Smithsonian's National Museum of Natural History to Build New Dinosaur Hall &#124; Newsdesk |publisher=Newsdesk.si.edu |date=May 3, 2012 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = David Koch donates $35&nbsp;million to National Museum of Natural History for dinosaur hall|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/david-koch-donates-35-million-to-national-museum-of-natural-history-for-dinosaur-hall/2012/05/03/gIQAIjT3yT_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 3, 2012|access-date=January 24, 2016 |issn=0190-8286|first=Jacqueline|last=Trescott}}</ref>\n\nKoch was also a benefactor of the [[Deerfield Academy]], his alma mater. The Academy's natatorium, science center, and field house are named after him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.recorder.com/DA-alum-David-Koch-dies-27936537|title=DA alum David Koch dies|date=August 24, 2019|website=Greenfield Recorder}}</ref> Koch was named the Academy's first Lifetime Trustee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/08/30/covert-operations|title=The Koch Brothers\u2019 Covert Ops|first=Jane|last=Mayer|date=August 23, 2010|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref>\n\nKoch gave $10&nbsp;million to the [[Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Koch Brothers' Ten Most Shocking Power Grabs|url=http://thefederalist.com/2015/02/02/the-koch-brothers-ten-most-shocking-power-grabs/|access-date=February 14, 2016 |last=Media|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Medical research ===\nKoch said his biggest contributions go toward a \"moon shot\" campaign to finding the cure for cancer, according to his profile on [[Forbes]].<ref name=\"forbes\" /> Between 1998 and 2012, Koch contributed at least $395&nbsp;million to medical research causes and institutions.<ref name=PhilMag>{{Cite news|last=Sparks|first=Evan|title=The Team Builder |url=http://www.philanthropyroundtable.org/topic/excellence_in_philanthropy/the_team_builder|access-date=September 26, 2012 |newspaper=[[Philanthropy (magazine)|Philanthropy]]|date=Summer 2012}}</ref>\n\nKoch was a member of the board of directors of the [[Prostate Cancer Foundation]] and contributed $41&nbsp;million to the foundation, including $5&nbsp;million to a collaborative project in the field of [[nanotechnology]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pcf.org/site/c.leJRIROrEpH/b.5801629/k.8E55/David_H_Koch_8211_Prostate_Cancer_Foundation_NanoMedicine_Gift_Announced.htm |title=David H. Koch \u2013 Prostate Cancer Foundation Nano-Medicine Gift Announced |publisher=PCF.org |date=October 12, 2007 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Dolan|first1=Kerry|title=Warren Buffett Has Plenty of Company Among Powerful in Battling Prostate Cancer|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2012/04/17/warren-buffett-has-plenty-of-company-among-prostate-cancer-survivors/#66538e462c78|work=Forbes|access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> An eponym of the David H. Koch Chair of the Prostate Cancer Foundation, the position is held by [[Dr. Jonathan Simons]].<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Clinical Data for World's First Truly Non-Invasive Prostate Cancer Test Published in JAMA Oncology |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20160412005315/en/Clinical-Data-World%E2%80%99s-Non-Invasive-Prostate-Cancer-Test |publisher=Exosome Diagnostics|access-date=April 12, 2018|date=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Koch gave $20&nbsp;million to [[Johns Hopkins University]] [[Johns Hopkins School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] in [[Baltimore]] for cancer research. The building he financed was named the David H. Koch Cancer Research Building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/news/media/releases/david_koch_gives_20_million_for_hopkins_cancer_research|title=David Koch Gives $20 Million for Hopkins Cancer Research|publisher=hopkinsmedicine.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he contributed $100&nbsp;million to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology for the construction of a new {{Convert|350000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} research and technology facility to serve as the home of the [[David H. Koch Institute for Integrative Cancer Research]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kochfamilyfoundations.org/pdfs/Koch%2002-2008%20%20Spectrum%20EmpathyforOthers.pdf |format=PDF |title=Empathy For Others |publisher=Kochfamilyfoundations.org |access-date=June 10, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311202401/http://www.kochfamilyfoundations.org/pdfs/Koch%2002-2008%20%20Spectrum%20EmpathyforOthers.pdf |archive-date=March 11, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> From the time he joined the MIT Corporation in 1988, Koch gave at least $185&nbsp;million to MIT,<ref name=PhilMag /> $15&nbsp;million to [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]] [[Weill Cornell Medical College of Cornell University|Weill Cornell Medical Center]]<ref name=\"WSJ 20071009\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119189124817352914|title=Institutional Gift, With a Catch|first=Sally | last=Beatty |date=October 9, 2007|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url-access=subscription}}</ref> and $30&nbsp;million to the [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York City.<ref name=\"WSJ 20071009\" /> The same year, he donated $25&nbsp;million to the [[University of Texas M. D. Anderson Cancer Center]] in [[Houston]] to establish the David Koch Center for Applied Research in Genitourinary Cancers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Koch-gives-18-million-gift-to-M-D-Anderson-1800063.php|title=Koch gives $18 million gift to M.D. Anderson|date=2007-11-10|website=Houston Chronicle|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Koch gave $5&nbsp;million to the House Ear Institute, in Los Angeles, to create a center for hearing restoration,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> and $25&nbsp;million to the [[Hospital for Special Surgery]] in New York City<ref>{{Cite web|title=No. 45: David H. Koch|url=http://philanthropy.com/article/No-45-David-H-Koch/126132/|publisher=The Chronicle of Philanthropy|access-date=October 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joshfriedland.com/pdfs/HSS_DtoR_13_Fall_2007.pdf |format=PDF |title=Discovery to Recovery : Clinical and Research Highlights at HSS |date=2007 |publisher=Joshfriedland.com |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\nIn 2013, he gave $100&nbsp;million to [[NewYork\u2013Presbyterian Hospital]], the largest philanthropic donation in its history, beginning a $2&nbsp;billion campaign to conclude in 2019 for a new [[ambulatory care]] center and renovation the infrastructure of the hospital's five sites.<ref name=NYPresb>{{Cite web|last=NewYork-Presbyterian|title=NewYork-Presbyterian Announces $100 Million Donation from David H. Koch \u2013 Largest in Hospital's History \u2013 to Fund Outpatient Facility on Manhattan's East Side|url=http://nyp.org/news/hospital/David-Koch-Donation-2013.html|access-date=June 1, 2013|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he committed $150&nbsp;million to [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in [[New York City]] to build the David H. Koch Center for Cancer Care, which will be housed in a 23-story building in development between East 73rd and 74th Streets overlooking the [[FDR Drive]]. The center will combine state-of-the-art cancer treatment in an environment that supports patients, families, and caregivers. The building will include flexible personal and community spaces, educational offerings, and opportunities for physical exercise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mskcc.org/press-releases/msk-receives-gift-150-million-david-koch-patient-facility |title=Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center Receives Record Gift of $150&nbsp;million from David Koch for Innovative Patient Care Facility|access-date=May 20, 2015|date=May 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Wealth ==\nKoch was the fourth-richest person in the United States in 2012 and was the wealthiest resident of [[New York City]] in 2013.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{Cite news |agency=Forbes|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/david-koch|title=David Koch \u2013 Forbes |date=March 9, 2011 |access-date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> As of June 2019, Koch was ranked as the 11th-richest person in the world (tied with his brother Charles), with a fortune of $50.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/david-koch/ |title=David Koch |access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Fred with David and Julia Koch (1518448020).jpg|thumb|Fred Thompson poses with David Koch and his wife Julia.]]\nKoch married Julia Flesher in 1996.<ref name=\"Woman Ascending\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/11/magazine/woman-ascending-a-marble-staircase.html?pagewanted=all |title=Woman Ascending A Marble Staircase |first=Elizabeth | last=Bumiller |work=The New York Times |date=January 11, 1998 |access-date=August 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"weddings\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/26/style/weddings-julia-m-flesher-david-h-koch.html |title=Weddings: Julia M. Flesher, David H. Koch |work=The New York Times |date=May 26, 1996 |access-date=September 2, 2010}}</ref> They had three children.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=McFadden |first1=Robert D. |title=David Koch, Billionaire Who Fueled Right-Wing Movement, Dies at 79 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/us/david-koch-dead.html |access-date=August 24, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1991, Koch was a passenger on board [[US Airways|USAir]] Flight 1493 when it [[Los Angeles runway disaster|collided with another aircraft]] on a runway at [[Los Angeles International Airport]], killing 35 people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/03/07/opinion/last-in-line-for-the-exit.html|title='Last in Line for the Exit'|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1991-03-07}}</ref> Koch survived and said in an interview in 2014 that it helped change his life and prompted him to become \"tremendously philanthropic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/video/david-koch-plane-crash-helped-change-life-27598921|title=David Koch on the Plane Crash That Helped Change His Life|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=2014-12-15}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]]' death in 1994, Koch purchased her 15-room apartment at [[1040 Fifth Avenue]] and in 2006 resold it to billionaire [[Glenn Dubin]]. Koch then moved to Onassis's childhood NYC home, [[740 Park Avenue]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2006/06/jackie-flat-gets-32-m-2/|title=Jackie Flat Gets $32 M.|date=June 26, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Koch was diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]]. He underwent radiation, surgery, and hormone therapy, but the cancer repeatedly returned. Koch said he believed his experience with cancer encouraged him to fund medical research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/08/david-koch-cause-of-death-cancer/|title=David Koch\u2019s Cause of Death: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|first=Alyssa|last=Choiniere|date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKoch died at his home in [[Southampton, New York]], on August 23, 2019, at the age of 79.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/us/david-koch-dead.html|title= David Koch, Billionaire Who Fueled Right-Wing Movement, Dies at 79|work = [[The New York Times]]|date = August 23, 2019|access-date = August 23, 2019|last = McFadden|first = Robert D.|authorlink = Robert D. McFadden}}</ref> Koch's wife, Julia Koch, and their three children inherited a 42% stake in Koch Industries from Koch upon his death.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/julia-koch/?list=forbes-400#2fab53562b9c|title=Julia Koch & family|access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Koch family]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{C-SPAN|davidkoch}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101103024037/http://www.influenceexplorer.com/individual/koch-david/741672ab1e0a4314be416ce3cfc2afbc Political contributions] from ''Influence Explorer'' at the [[Sunlight Foundation]]\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/press/ReportView.phtml?r=434 Names in the News: David and Charles Koch] at FollowTheMoney.org\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/k/david_h_koch Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/sonsofwichitahow0000schu|first=Daniel|last=Schulman|title=Sons of Wichita|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=978-1455518739|date=May 20, 2014|url-access=registration}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[David Bergland]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] [[List of United States Libertarian Party presidential tickets|nominee]] for [[Vice President of the United States]]|years=[[1980 United States presidential election|1980]]}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[James A. Lewis|Jim Lewis]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Libertarian Party (United States)}}\n{{1980 United States presidential election}}\n{{Koch family}}\n{{Koch Industries}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koch, David}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:1980 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American political fundraisers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kansas]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Cato Institute people]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deerfield Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Drug policy reform activists]]\n[[Category:Engineers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Koch family|David Koch]]\n[[Category:Libertarian Party (United States) vice presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:MIT Engineers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Libertarians]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Wichita, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Wichita, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Survivors of aviation accidents or incidents]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Marquardtika", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Koch"}
{"title_page": "Hate speech laws in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "[[Hate speech]] laws in [[England and Wales]] are found in several statutes. Expressions of hatred toward someone on account of that person's colour, race, disability, nationality (including citizenship), ethnic or national origin, religion, gender identity, or sexual orientation is forbidden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statutelaw.gov.uk/content.aspx?activeTextDocId=2236942|title=Public Order Act 1986|website=www.statutelaw.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2006/ukpga_20060001_en_1|title=Racial and Religious Hatred Act 2006|website=www.opsi.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2008/pdf/ukpga_20080004_en.pdf|title=Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cps.gov.uk/hate-crime|title=Crown Prosecution Service: Hate Crime}}</ref> Any communication which is threatening or abusive, and is intended to harass, alarm, or distress someone is forbidden.<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1994/Ukpga_19940033_en_1.htm Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994].</ref> The penalties for hate speech include fines, imprisonment, or both.<ref>Besides \"hate speech\" laws, the United Kingdom has also [[hate crime]] laws. For England, Wales, and Scotland, the [[Crime and Disorder Act 1998]] makes hateful behaviour towards a victim based on the victim\u2019s membership (or presumed membership) in a racial group an \"aggravating factor\" for the purpose of sentencing in respect of specified crimes. A \"racial group\" is a group of persons defined by reference to race, colour, nationality (including citizenship) or ethnic or national origins. The specified crimes are assault, criminal damage, offences under the Public Order Act 1986, and offences under the Protection from Harassment Act 1997.http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2003/uksi_20032267_en.pdf</ref>\n\nThe Police and CPS have formulated a definition of hate crimes and hate incidents, with hate speech forming a subset of these. Something is a hate incident if the victim or anyone else think it was motivated by hostility or prejudice based on: disability, race, religion, transgender identity or sexual orientation. A hate incident becomes a hate crime if it crosses the boundary of criminality.<ref>https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/law-and-courts/discrimination/hate-crime/what-are-hate-incidents-and-hate-crime/</ref>\n\nSome United Kingdom statutes apply in Scotland and Northern Ireland. The Scottish government has held an independent review of hate crime laws which it intends to use as the basis for a wider consultation on new legislation.<ref>''[https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/scottish-judge-calls-for-age-gender-offences-to-be-hate-crimes-1-4748050 Scottish Judge calls for age, gender offences to be hate crimes]'', The Scotsman May 2018</ref>\n\n==Statutes==\nIn England and Wales and Scotland the [[Public Order Act 1986]] prohibits, by its Part 3, expressions of racial hatred, which is defined as hatred against a group of persons by reason of the group's colour, race, nationality (including citizenship) or ethnic or national origins. Section 18 of the Act says:\n<blockquote>\nA person who uses threatening, abusive or insulting words or behaviour, or displays any written material which is threatening, abusive or insulting, is guilty of an offence if\u2014\n\n::(a) he intends thereby to stir up racial hatred, or\n\n::(b) having regard to all the circumstances racial hatred is likely to be stirred up thereby.\n</blockquote>\nOffences under Part 3 carry a maximum sentence of seven years imprisonment or a fine or both.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statutelaw.gov.uk/content.aspx?LegType=All+Legislation&title=Public+Order+Act&Year=1986&searchEnacted=0&extentMatchOnly=0&confersPower=0&blanketAmendment=0&sortAlpha=0&TYPE=QS&PageNumber=1&NavFrom=0&parentActiveTextDocId=2236942&ActiveTextDocId=2237025&filesize=2382#1365595|title=Public Order Act 1986|website=www.statutelaw.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994]] inserted Section 4A into the Public Order Act 1986. That part prohibits anyone from causing alarm or distress. Section 4A states, in part:\n<blockquote>\n(1) A person is guilty of an offence if, with intent to cause a person harassment, alarm or distress, he\u2014\n\n::(a) uses threatening, abusive or insulting words or behaviour, or disorderly behaviour, or\n\n::(b) displays any writing, sign or other visible representation which is threatening, abusive or insulting,\nthereby causing that or another person harassment, alarm or distress.\n\n...\n\n(5) A person guilty of an offence under this section is liable on summary conviction to imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months or to a fine not exceeding level 5 on the [[standard scale]] or to both.<ref>http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1994/Ukpga_19940033_en_1.htm Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe [[Racial and Religious Hatred Act 2006]] amended the Public Order Act 1986 by adding Part 3A. That Part says, \"A person who uses threatening words or behaviour, or displays any written material which is threatening, is guilty of an offence if he intends thereby to stir up religious hatred.\" The Part protects freedom of expression by stating in Section 29J:\n<blockquote>\nNothing in this Part shall be read or given effect in a way which prohibits or restricts discussion, criticism or expressions of antipathy, dislike, ridicule, insult or abuse of particular religions or the beliefs or practices of their adherents, or of any other belief system or the beliefs or practices of its adherents, or proselytising or urging adherents of a different religion or belief system to cease practising their religion or belief system.\n</blockquote>\nThe [[Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008]] amended Part 3A of the Public Order Act 1986. The amended Part 3A adds, for England and Wales, the offence of inciting hatred on the ground of sexual orientation. All the offences in Part 3 attach to the following acts: the use of words or behaviour or display of written material, publishing or distributing written material, the public performance of a play, distributing, showing or playing a recording, broadcasting or including a programme in a programme service, and possession of inflammatory material. In the circumstances of hatred based on religious belief or on sexual orientation, the relevant act (namely, words, behaviour, written material, or recordings, or programme) must be threatening and not just abusive or insulting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2008/en/08en04-g.htm|title=Legislation.gov.uk|website=www.opsi.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe Football Offences Act 1991 (amended by the Football (Offences and Disorder) Act 1999) forbids indecent or racialist chanting at designated football matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/ACTS/acts1999/en/ukpgaen_19990021_en_1|title=Explanatory Notes to Football (Offences and Disorder) Act 1999|first=Home|last=Office|website=www.opsi.gov.uk}}</ref> \n\nThe use of prisons to regulate hate speech has been critiqued from a normative perspective<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Baker |first1=Dennis |last2=Zhao |first2=Lucy |title=he Normativity of Using Prison to Control Hate Speech: The Hollowness of Waldron's Harm Theory |journal=New Criminal Law Review |date=2013 |volume=16 |issue=4}}</ref>.\n\n==Reform Section 5 campaign==\nIn 2012, a campaign was launched by the [[Christian Institute]] to remove the word \"insulting\" from section 5 of the Public Order Act. The campaign was backed by a number of high-profile activists including comedian [[Rowan Atkinson]] and former Shadow Home Secretary [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]. On 12 December 2012, the House of Lords voted in favour of amending the Public Order Act to remove the word \"insulting\". In January 2013, the government announced that it would accept the amendment, despite having previously opposed it. The amendment to the Public Order Act was duly passed into law, as section 57 of the Crime and Courts Act 2013.[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/22/section/57/enacted] Section 57 of the Act came into force on 1 February 2014.<ref>Statutory Instruments 2013/2981 art. 3</ref>\n\n==Selected cases==\nOn 13 October 2001, [[Harry Hammond]], an evangelist, was arrested and charged under section 5 of the Public Order Act (1986) because he had displayed to people in [[Bournemouth]] a large  sign bearing the words \"Jesus Gives Peace, Jesus is Alive, Stop Immorality, Stop Homosexuality, Stop Lesbianism, Jesus is Lord\". In April 2002, a magistrate convicted Hammond, fined him \u00a3300, and ordered him to pay costs of \u00a3395.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/hate1.html |title=Incitement to Religious Hatred - A Gag to the Gospel |last=Mullins |first=Mark |date=January 2005 |publisher=Christian Voice |accessdate=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719220651/http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/hate1.html |archivedate=19 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christian.org.uk/rel_liberties/cases/harry_hammond.htm|title=Street preacher convicted by magistrates for displaying a sign saying homosexuality is immoral|date=7 July 2006|publisher=The Christian Institute|accessdate=3 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510150230/http://www.christian.org.uk/rel_liberties/cases/harry_hammond.htm|archivedate=10 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,200-1415201,00.html|title=Hatred is no play on words|date=28 December 2004|publisher=TimesOnline|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 September 2006, [[Christian Voice (UK)|Stephen Green]] was arrested in [[Cardiff]] for distributing pamphlets which called sexual activity between members of the same sex a [[sin]]. On 28 September 2006, the Crown advised Cardiff Magistrates Court that it would not proceed with the prosecution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/5388626.stm|title=Anti-gay leaflets charge dropped|date=28 September 2006|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/Press/press021.html |title=Cardiff   'Mardi Gras' Evangelist Charges Dropped |date=28 September 2006 |publisher=Christian Voice |accessdate=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728003037/http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/Press/press021.html |archivedate=28 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 2009, Mr Justice Richard Clancy, sitting at Liverpool Magistrates' Court, acquitted Ben and Sharon Vogelenzang, hoteliers, of charges under the Public Order Act 1986 and under the Crime and Disorder Act 1998. The Vogelensangs were charged after a guest at their hotel, Ericka Tazi, complained that the Vogelenzangs had insulted her after she appeared in a [[hijab]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article6950322.ece|title=Hotelier Ben Vogelenzang cleared of insulting Muslim guest|last=Jenkins|first=Russell|date=9 December 2009|publisher=The Sunday Times|accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2010, a jury returned a verdict of guilty against Harry Taylor, who was charged under Part 4A of the Public Order Act 1986. Taylor was charged because he left anti-religious cartoons in the prayer-room of Liverpool's John Lennon Airport on three occasions in 2008. The airport chaplain, who was insulted, offended, and alarmed by the cartoons, called the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/ni/2010/03/militant_atheist_found_guilt_o.html|title=BBC - Will & Testament: \"Militant Atheist\" found guilty of religious harassment|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/regional-news/2010/03/03/atheist-accused-of-leaving-insulting-religious-images-in-liverpool-s-john-lennon-airport-prayer-room-100252-25948815/|title=Liverpool Echo: Latest Liverpool and Merseyside news, sports and what's on|website=www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediawatchwatch.org.uk/2010/03/05/the-blasphemy-law-is-back/|title=The Blasphemy law is back - MediaWatchWatch|website=www.mediawatchwatch.org.uk}}</ref> On 23 April 2010, Judge Charles James of Liverpool Crown Court sentenced Taylor to a six-month term of imprisonment suspended for two years, made him subject to a five-year Anti-Social Behaviour Order ([[ASBO]]) (which bans him from carrying religiously offensive material in a public place), ordered him to perform 100 hours of unpaid work, and ordered him to pay \u00a3250 costs. Taylor was convicted of similar offences in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/merseyside/8640048.stm|title=John Lennon Airport sexual image atheist gets Asbo|date=23 April 2010|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2010, police arrested Dale McAlpine, a Christian preacher, of [[Workington]] in [[Cumbria]], for saying that homosexual conduct was a [[sin]]. On 14 May 2010, the Crown decided not to prosecute McAlpine.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Evans\n  | first = Martin\n  | title = Christian preacher arrested for saying gays were sinful has charges dropped\n  | publisher = Telegraph.co.uk\n  | date = 14 May 2010\n  | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7725797/Christian-preacher-arrested-for-saying-gays-were-sinful-has-charges-dropped.html\n  | accessdate = 15 May 2010}}</ref> Later still the police apologised to McAlpine for arresting him at all, and paid him several thousand pounds compensation.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=McGowen \n |first=Pamela \n |title=Street preacher wins compensation after Cumbria police wrongful arrest \n |publisher=www.newsandstar.co.uk \n |date=3 June 2010 \n |url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/street-preacher-wins-compensation-after-cumbria-police-wrongful-arrest-1.793064 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107170832/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/street-preacher-wins-compensation-after-cumbria-police-wrongful-arrest-1.793064 \n |archivedate=7 November 2014 \n}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2018, Scottish YouTuber [[Mark Meechan]] of [[Coatbridge]], [[North Lanarkshire]] was fined \u00a3800 after being found \"grossly offensive\" for posting a YouTube video that was viewed over 3 million times depicting him training his girlfriend's pug to respond to the phrase \"Sieg Heil\" by lifting his paw in a [[Nazi salute]].\n<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Dearden\n  | first = Lizzie\n  | title = Man who taught girlfriend's pet pug dog to perform Nazi salutes fined \u00a3800\n  | publisher = independent.co.uk\n  | date = 23 April 2018\n  | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/count-dankula-nazi-pug-salutes-mark-meechan-fine-sentenced-a8317751.html\n  | accessdate = 15 May 2018}}</ref> Tory MP [[Philip Davies]] requested a review of freedom of expression in parliament in response to the conviction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/yorkshire-mp-philip-davies-backs-ricky-gervais-in-freedom-of-speech-row-after-youtuber-count-dankula-a3796961.html|title=Yorkshire MP Philip Davies backs Ricky Gervais in freedom of speech row after YouTuber Count Dankula found guilty of making 'highly offensive' video|first=Martin|last=Coulter|publisher=The Evening Standard|date=2018-03-23|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref> Comedians [[Ricky Gervais]] and [[David Baddiel]] tweeted in support of Meechan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-43478925|title=Man guilty of hate crime for filming pug's 'Nazi salutes'|publisher=BBC|date=2018-03-20|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/youtuber-count-dankula-found-guilty-of-hate-crime-for-teaching-pet-pug-nazi-salute-a3794926.html|title=YouTuber Count Dankula is found guilty of hate crime after teaching pet pug 'Nazi salute'|first=Martin|last=Coulter|publisher=The Standard|date=2018-03-20|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/25/being-offensive-should-not-be-illegal-in-society-that-defends-free-speech|title=The 'Nazi pug': giving offence is inevitable and often necessary in a plural society|author=[[Kenan Malik]]|publisher=The Guardian|date=2018-03-25|accessdate=2018-03-27}}</ref> [[Jonathan Pie|Tom Walker]], [[Shappi Khorsandi]], and [[Stephen Fry]] defended Meechan and criticised other comedians for their silence on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiked-online.com/newsite/article/lets-stand-up-for-the-right-to-be-offensive/21258#.WsrcujcpDxg|title=Let's stand up for the right to be offensive|first=Andrew|last=Doyle|publisher=Spiked|date=2018-03-28|accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/count-dankula-freedom-of-speech-comedy-joke-iran-offended-a8270631.html|title=The conviction of Count Dankula sets a dangerous precedent for freedom of speech|first=Shappi|last=Khorsandi|publisher=The Independent|date=2018-03-23|accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/jonathan-pie-defends-youtuber-convicted-140909534.html|title=Jonathan Pie Defends YouTuber Convicted for Nazi Pug Video|publisher=Yahoo News|date=2018-03-26|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref> Meechan, who plans to appeal, was sentenced to pay an \u00a3800 fine on 23 April 2018.<ref name=dearden>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/count-dankula-nazi-pug-salutes-mark-meechan-fine-sentenced-a8317751.html|title=Man who taught girlfriend's pet pug dog to perform Nazi salutes fined \u00a3800|first=Lizzie|last=Dearden|publisher=The Independent|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Man who filmed dog giving Nazi salutes fined \u00a3800|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/apr/23/man-who-filmed-dog-giving-nazi-salutes-fined|accessdate=23 April 2018|work=the Guardian|date=23 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> A crowd of about 500 people protested the move in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/homenews/16178725.Video__Row_over_police_filming_London_protest_over_Scots__Nazi_dog__creator_conviction/|title=Row over police filming London protest over Scots 'Nazi dog' creator conviction|first=Martin|last=Williams|publisher=The Sunday Herald|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, 19-year old [[Croxteth]] resident Chelsea Russell quoted a line from Snap Dogg's song \"I'm Trippin'\" on her [[Instagram]] page. The line, which read \"Kill a snitch nigga, rob a rich nigga\", was copied from a friend's page as part of a tribute to Frankie Murphy who was killed in a car accident at age 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/u-k-woman-charged-with-a-hate-crime-for-posting-grossly-offensive-rap-lyrics-on-instagram|title=U.K. Woman Charged With A Hate Crime For Posting \"Grossly Offensive\" Rap Lyrics On Instagram|first=Chris|last=Mech|publisher=Genius|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/04/23/she-posted-rap-lyrics-to-remember-a-dead|title=She Posted Rap Lyrics to Remember a Dead Teen, So the U.K. Prosecuted Her for Hate Speech|first=Scott|last=Shackford|publisher=Reason|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> Hate crime investigators were alerted to the presence of the slur and charged Russell with \"sending a grossly offensive message by means of a public electronic communications network\". Defence lawyer Carole Clarke stated that she received a request from one of the arresting officers that the word \"[[nigga]]\", the subject of the trial, not be used in court.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/woman-who-posted-rap-lyrics-14543694|title=Woman who posted rap lyrics as tribute on Instagram guilty of sending offensive message|first=Tom|last=Duffy|publisher=The Liverpool Echo|date=2018-04-17|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> In April 2018, District Judge Jack McGarva found Russell guilty and delivered a sentence which included a \u00a3585 fine, a curfew and an ankle monitoring bracelet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-merseyside-43816921|title=Woman guilty of 'racist' Snap Dogg rap lyric Instagram post|publisher=BBC|date=2018-04-19|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> However, Russell's conviction was overturned by Liverpool Crown Court on 21 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Docking |first1=Neil |title=This teen with Asperger's was prosecuted - for Instagramming N-word rap lyrics |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/teen-prosecuted-n-word-rap-15874476 |website=liverpoolecho |accessdate=9 June 2019 |date=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Hate speech}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://pa.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2011/07/07/pa.gsr022.full.pdf+html \"'If a Charge was Brought Against a Saintly Religious Leader Whose Intention Was to Save Souls . . .': An Analysis of UK Parliamentary Debates over Incitement to Hatred on the Grounds of Sexual Orientation\"]. 2011 academic article that considers the creation of the hate speech offence in the Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008\n\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Hate speech]]\n[[Category:Censorship in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "[[Hate speech]] laws in [[England and Wales]] are found in several statutes. Expressions of hatred toward someone on account of that person's colour, race, disability, nationality (including citizenship), ethnic or national origin, religion, gender identity, or sexual orientation is forbidden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statutelaw.gov.uk/content.aspx?activeTextDocId=2236942|title=Public Order Act 1986|website=www.statutelaw.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2006/ukpga_20060001_en_1|title=Racial and Religious Hatred Act 2006|website=www.opsi.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2008/pdf/ukpga_20080004_en.pdf|title=Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cps.gov.uk/hate-crime|title=Crown Prosecution Service: Hate Crime}}</ref> Any communication which is threatening or abusive, and is intended to harass, alarm, or distress someone is forbidden.<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1994/Ukpga_19940033_en_1.htm Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994].</ref> The penalties for hate speech include fines, imprisonment, or both.<ref>Besides \"hate speech\" laws, the United Kingdom has also [[hate crime]] laws. For England, Wales, and Scotland, the [[Crime and Disorder Act 1998]] makes hateful behaviour towards a victim based on the victim\u2019s membership (or presumed membership) in a racial group an \"aggravating factor\" for the purpose of sentencing in respect of specified crimes. A \"racial group\" is a group of persons defined by reference to race, colour, nationality (including citizenship) or ethnic or national origins. The specified crimes are assault, criminal damage, offences under the Public Order Act 1986, and offences under the Protection from Harassment Act 1997.http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2003/uksi_20032267_en.pdf</ref>\n\nThe Police and CPS have formulated a definition of hate crimes and hate incidents, with hate speech forming a subset of these. Something is a hate incident if the victim or anyone else think it was motivated by hostility or prejudice based on: disability, race, religion, transgender identity or sexual orientation. A hate incident becomes a hate crime if it crosses the boundary of criminality.<ref>https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/law-and-courts/discrimination/hate-crime/what-are-hate-incidents-and-hate-crime/</ref>\n\nSome United Kingdom statutes apply in Scotland and Northern Ireland. The Scottish government has held an independent review of hate crime laws which it intends to use as the basis for a wider consultation on new legislation.<ref>''[https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/scottish-judge-calls-for-age-gender-offences-to-be-hate-crimes-1-4748050 Scottish Judge calls for age, gender offences to be hate crimes]'', The Scotsman May 2018</ref>\n\n==Statutes==\nIn England and Wales and Scotland the [[Public Order Act 1986]] prohibits, by its Part 3, expressions of racial hatred, which is defined as hatred against a group of persons by reason of the group's colour, race, nationality (including citizenship) or ethnic or national origins. Section 18 of the Act says:\n<blockquote>\nA person who uses threatening, abusive or insulting words or behaviour, or displays any written material which is threatening, abusive or insulting, is guilty of an offence if\u2014\n\n::(a) he intends thereby to stir up racial hatred, or\n\n::(b) having regard to all the circumstances racial hatred is likely to be stirred up thereby.\n</blockquote>\nOffences under Part 3 carry a maximum sentence of seven years imprisonment or a fine or both.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statutelaw.gov.uk/content.aspx?LegType=All+Legislation&title=Public+Order+Act&Year=1986&searchEnacted=0&extentMatchOnly=0&confersPower=0&blanketAmendment=0&sortAlpha=0&TYPE=QS&PageNumber=1&NavFrom=0&parentActiveTextDocId=2236942&ActiveTextDocId=2237025&filesize=2382#1365595|title=Public Order Act 1986|website=www.statutelaw.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994]] inserted Section 4A into the Public Order Act 1986. That part prohibits anyone from causing alarm or distress. Section 4A states, in part:\n<blockquote>\n(1) A person is guilty of an offence if, with intent to cause a person harassment, alarm or distress, he\u2014\n\n::(a) uses threatening, abusive or insulting words or behaviour, or disorderly behaviour, or\n\n::(b) displays any writing, sign or other visible representation which is threatening, abusive or insulting,\nthereby causing that or another person harassment, alarm or distress.\n\n...\n\n(5) A person guilty of an offence under this section is liable on summary conviction to imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months or to a fine not exceeding level 5 on the [[standard scale]] or to both.<ref>http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts1994/Ukpga_19940033_en_1.htm Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe [[Racial and Religious Hatred Act 2006]] amended the Public Order Act 1986 by adding Part 3A. That Part says, \"A person who uses threatening words or behaviour, or displays any written material which is threatening, is guilty of an offence if he intends thereby to stir up religious hatred.\" The Part protects freedom of expression by stating in Section 29J:\n<blockquote>\nNothing in this Part shall be read or given effect in a way which prohibits or restricts discussion, criticism or expressions of antipathy, dislike, ridicule, insult or abuse of particular religions or the beliefs or practices of their adherents, or of any other belief system or the beliefs or practices of its adherents, or proselytising or urging adherents of a different religion or belief system to cease practising their religion or belief system.\n</blockquote>\nThe [[Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008]] amended Part 3A of the Public Order Act 1986. The amended Part 3A adds, for England and Wales, the offence of inciting hatred on the ground of sexual orientation. All the offences in Part 3 attach to the following acts: the use of words or behaviour or display of written material, publishing or distributing written material, the public performance of a play, distributing, showing or playing a recording, broadcasting or including a programme in a programme service, and possession of inflammatory material. In the circumstances of hatred based on religious belief or on sexual orientation, the relevant act (namely, words, behaviour, written material, or recordings, or programme) must be threatening and not just abusive or insulting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2008/en/08en04-g.htm|title=Legislation.gov.uk|website=www.opsi.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe Football Offences Act 1991 (amended by the Football (Offences and Disorder) Act 1999) forbids indecent or racialist chanting at designated football matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/ACTS/acts1999/en/ukpgaen_19990021_en_1|title=Explanatory Notes to Football (Offences and Disorder) Act 1999|first=Home|last=Office|website=www.opsi.gov.uk}}</ref> \n\nThe use of prisons to regulate hate speech has been critiqued from a normative perspective <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Baker |first1=Dennis |last2=Zhao |first2=Lucy |title=he Normativity of Using Prison to Control Hate Speech: The Hollowness of Waldron's Harm Theory |journal=New Criminal Law Review |date=2013 |volume=16 |issue=4}}</ref>.\n\n==Reform Section 5 campaign==\nIn 2012, a campaign was launched by the [[Christian Institute]] to remove the word \"insulting\" from section 5 of the Public Order Act. The campaign was backed by a number of high-profile activists including comedian [[Rowan Atkinson]] and former Shadow Home Secretary [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]. On 12 December 2012, the House of Lords voted in favour of amending the Public Order Act to remove the word \"insulting\". In January 2013, the government announced that it would accept the amendment, despite having previously opposed it. The amendment to the Public Order Act was duly passed into law, as section 57 of the Crime and Courts Act 2013.[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2013/22/section/57/enacted] Section 57 of the Act came into force on 1 February 2014.<ref>Statutory Instruments 2013/2981 art. 3</ref>\n\n==Selected cases==\nOn 13 October 2001, [[Harry Hammond]], an evangelist, was arrested and charged under section 5 of the Public Order Act (1986) because he had displayed to people in [[Bournemouth]] a large  sign bearing the words \"Jesus Gives Peace, Jesus is Alive, Stop Immorality, Stop Homosexuality, Stop Lesbianism, Jesus is Lord\". In April 2002, a magistrate convicted Hammond, fined him \u00a3300, and ordered him to pay costs of \u00a3395.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/hate1.html |title=Incitement to Religious Hatred - A Gag to the Gospel |last=Mullins |first=Mark |date=January 2005 |publisher=Christian Voice |accessdate=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719220651/http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/hate1.html |archivedate=19 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christian.org.uk/rel_liberties/cases/harry_hammond.htm|title=Street preacher convicted by magistrates for displaying a sign saying homosexuality is immoral|date=7 July 2006|publisher=The Christian Institute|accessdate=3 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510150230/http://www.christian.org.uk/rel_liberties/cases/harry_hammond.htm|archivedate=10 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,200-1415201,00.html|title=Hatred is no play on words|date=28 December 2004|publisher=TimesOnline|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 September 2006, [[Christian Voice (UK)|Stephen Green]] was arrested in [[Cardiff]] for distributing pamphlets which called sexual activity between members of the same sex a [[sin]]. On 28 September 2006, the Crown advised Cardiff Magistrates Court that it would not proceed with the prosecution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/5388626.stm|title=Anti-gay leaflets charge dropped|date=28 September 2006|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/Press/press021.html |title=Cardiff   'Mardi Gras' Evangelist Charges Dropped |date=28 September 2006 |publisher=Christian Voice |accessdate=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728003037/http://www.christianvoice.org.uk/Press/press021.html |archivedate=28 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 2009, Mr Justice Richard Clancy, sitting at Liverpool Magistrates' Court, acquitted Ben and Sharon Vogelenzang, hoteliers, of charges under the Public Order Act 1986 and under the Crime and Disorder Act 1998. The Vogelensangs were charged after a guest at their hotel, Ericka Tazi, complained that the Vogelenzangs had insulted her after she appeared in a [[hijab]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article6950322.ece|title=Hotelier Ben Vogelenzang cleared of insulting Muslim guest|last=Jenkins|first=Russell|date=9 December 2009|publisher=The Sunday Times|accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2010, a jury returned a verdict of guilty against Harry Taylor, who was charged under Part 4A of the Public Order Act 1986. Taylor was charged because he left anti-religious cartoons in the prayer-room of Liverpool's John Lennon Airport on three occasions in 2008. The airport chaplain, who was insulted, offended, and alarmed by the cartoons, called the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/ni/2010/03/militant_atheist_found_guilt_o.html|title=BBC - Will & Testament: \"Militant Atheist\" found guilty of religious harassment|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/regional-news/2010/03/03/atheist-accused-of-leaving-insulting-religious-images-in-liverpool-s-john-lennon-airport-prayer-room-100252-25948815/|title=Liverpool Echo: Latest Liverpool and Merseyside news, sports and what's on|website=www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediawatchwatch.org.uk/2010/03/05/the-blasphemy-law-is-back/|title=The Blasphemy law is back - MediaWatchWatch|website=www.mediawatchwatch.org.uk}}</ref> On 23 April 2010, Judge Charles James of Liverpool Crown Court sentenced Taylor to a six-month term of imprisonment suspended for two years, made him subject to a five-year Anti-Social Behaviour Order ([[ASBO]]) (which bans him from carrying religiously offensive material in a public place), ordered him to perform 100 hours of unpaid work, and ordered him to pay \u00a3250 costs. Taylor was convicted of similar offences in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/merseyside/8640048.stm|title=John Lennon Airport sexual image atheist gets Asbo|date=23 April 2010|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2010, police arrested Dale McAlpine, a Christian preacher, of [[Workington]] in [[Cumbria]], for saying that homosexual conduct was a [[sin]]. On 14 May 2010, the Crown decided not to prosecute McAlpine.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Evans\n  | first = Martin\n  | title = Christian preacher arrested for saying gays were sinful has charges dropped\n  | publisher = Telegraph.co.uk\n  | date = 14 May 2010\n  | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7725797/Christian-preacher-arrested-for-saying-gays-were-sinful-has-charges-dropped.html\n  | accessdate = 15 May 2010}}</ref> Later still the police apologised to McAlpine for arresting him at all, and paid him several thousand pounds compensation.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=McGowen \n |first=Pamela \n |title=Street preacher wins compensation after Cumbria police wrongful arrest \n |publisher=www.newsandstar.co.uk \n |date=3 June 2010 \n |url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/street-preacher-wins-compensation-after-cumbria-police-wrongful-arrest-1.793064 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107170832/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/street-preacher-wins-compensation-after-cumbria-police-wrongful-arrest-1.793064 \n |archivedate=7 November 2014 \n}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2018, Scottish YouTuber [[Mark Meechan]] of [[Coatbridge]], [[North Lanarkshire]] was fined \u00a3800 after being found \"grossly offensive\" for posting a YouTube video that was viewed over 3 million times depicting him training his girlfriend's pug to respond to the phrase \"Sieg Heil\" by lifting his paw in a [[Nazi salute]].\n<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = Dearden\n  | first = Lizzie\n  | title = Man who taught girlfriend's pet pug dog to perform Nazi salutes fined \u00a3800\n  | publisher = independent.co.uk\n  | date = 23 April 2018\n  | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/count-dankula-nazi-pug-salutes-mark-meechan-fine-sentenced-a8317751.html\n  | accessdate = 15 May 2018}}</ref> Tory MP [[Philip Davies]] requested a review of freedom of expression in parliament in response to the conviction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/yorkshire-mp-philip-davies-backs-ricky-gervais-in-freedom-of-speech-row-after-youtuber-count-dankula-a3796961.html|title=Yorkshire MP Philip Davies backs Ricky Gervais in freedom of speech row after YouTuber Count Dankula found guilty of making 'highly offensive' video|first=Martin|last=Coulter|publisher=The Evening Standard|date=2018-03-23|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref> Comedians [[Ricky Gervais]] and [[David Baddiel]] tweeted in support of Meechan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-43478925|title=Man guilty of hate crime for filming pug's 'Nazi salutes'|publisher=BBC|date=2018-03-20|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/youtuber-count-dankula-found-guilty-of-hate-crime-for-teaching-pet-pug-nazi-salute-a3794926.html|title=YouTuber Count Dankula is found guilty of hate crime after teaching pet pug 'Nazi salute'|first=Martin|last=Coulter|publisher=The Standard|date=2018-03-20|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/25/being-offensive-should-not-be-illegal-in-society-that-defends-free-speech|title=The 'Nazi pug': giving offence is inevitable and often necessary in a plural society|author=[[Kenan Malik]]|publisher=The Guardian|date=2018-03-25|accessdate=2018-03-27}}</ref> [[Jonathan Pie|Tom Walker]], [[Shappi Khorsandi]], and [[Stephen Fry]] defended Meechan and criticised other comedians for their silence on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiked-online.com/newsite/article/lets-stand-up-for-the-right-to-be-offensive/21258#.WsrcujcpDxg|title=Let's stand up for the right to be offensive|first=Andrew|last=Doyle|publisher=Spiked|date=2018-03-28|accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/count-dankula-freedom-of-speech-comedy-joke-iran-offended-a8270631.html|title=The conviction of Count Dankula sets a dangerous precedent for freedom of speech|first=Shappi|last=Khorsandi|publisher=The Independent|date=2018-03-23|accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/jonathan-pie-defends-youtuber-convicted-140909534.html|title=Jonathan Pie Defends YouTuber Convicted for Nazi Pug Video|publisher=Yahoo News|date=2018-03-26|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref> Meechan, who plans to appeal, was sentenced to pay an \u00a3800 fine on 23 April 2018.<ref name=dearden>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/count-dankula-nazi-pug-salutes-mark-meechan-fine-sentenced-a8317751.html|title=Man who taught girlfriend's pet pug dog to perform Nazi salutes fined \u00a3800|first=Lizzie|last=Dearden|publisher=The Independent|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Man who filmed dog giving Nazi salutes fined \u00a3800|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/apr/23/man-who-filmed-dog-giving-nazi-salutes-fined|accessdate=23 April 2018|work=the Guardian|date=23 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> A crowd of about 500 people protested the move in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/homenews/16178725.Video__Row_over_police_filming_London_protest_over_Scots__Nazi_dog__creator_conviction/|title=Row over police filming London protest over Scots 'Nazi dog' creator conviction|first=Martin|last=Williams|publisher=The Sunday Herald|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, 19-year old [[Croxteth]] resident Chelsea Russell quoted a line from Snap Dogg's song \"I'm Trippin'\" on her [[Instagram]] page. The line, which read \"Kill a snitch nigga, rob a rich nigga\", was copied from a friend's page as part of a tribute to Frankie Murphy who was killed in a car accident at age 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/u-k-woman-charged-with-a-hate-crime-for-posting-grossly-offensive-rap-lyrics-on-instagram|title=U.K. Woman Charged With A Hate Crime For Posting \"Grossly Offensive\" Rap Lyrics On Instagram|first=Chris|last=Mech|publisher=Genius|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/04/23/she-posted-rap-lyrics-to-remember-a-dead|title=She Posted Rap Lyrics to Remember a Dead Teen, So the U.K. Prosecuted Her for Hate Speech|first=Scott|last=Shackford|publisher=Reason|date=2018-04-23|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> Hate crime investigators were alerted to the presence of the slur and charged Russell with \"sending a grossly offensive message by means of a public electronic communications network\". Defence lawyer Carole Clarke stated that she received a request from one of the arresting officers that the word \"[[nigga]]\", the subject of the trial, not be used in court.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/woman-who-posted-rap-lyrics-14543694|title=Woman who posted rap lyrics as tribute on Instagram guilty of sending offensive message|first=Tom|last=Duffy|publisher=The Liverpool Echo|date=2018-04-17|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> In April 2018, District Judge Jack McGarva found Russell guilty and delivered a sentence which included a \u00a3585 fine, a curfew and an ankle monitoring bracelet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-merseyside-43816921|title=Woman guilty of 'racist' Snap Dogg rap lyric Instagram post|publisher=BBC|date=2018-04-19|accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> However, Russell's conviction was overturned by Liverpool Crown Court on 21 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Docking |first1=Neil |title=This teen with Asperger's was prosecuted - for Instagramming N-word rap lyrics |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/teen-prosecuted-n-word-rap-15874476 |website=liverpoolecho |accessdate=9 June 2019 |date=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Hate speech}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://pa.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2011/07/07/pa.gsr022.full.pdf+html \"'If a Charge was Brought Against a Saintly Religious Leader Whose Intention Was to Save Souls . . .': An Analysis of UK Parliamentary Debates over Incitement to Hatred on the Grounds of Sexual Orientation\"]. 2011 academic article that considers the creation of the hate speech offence in the Criminal Justice and Immigration Act 2008\n\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Hate speech]]\n[[Category:Censorship in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "HalMartin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatutes:wikify formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hate_speech_laws_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
